top1: Harry Potter star Daniel Radcliffe turns 18 on Monday. He gains access to a reported Â£20 million ($41.1 million) fortune. Radcliffe's earnings from the first five Potter films have been held in a trust fund. Details of how he'll mark his landmark birthday are under wraps.

Judge Steven Leifman is an advocate for justice and the mentally ill. About one-third of all people in Miami-Dade county jails are mentally ill, he says. He says the sheer volume is overwhelming the system. Starting in 2008, many inmates will be sent to a new mental health facility.

"I probably had a 30-, 35-foot free fall," survivor Gary Babineau says. Dr. John Hink says he saw dozens of people lying dazed on an expansive deck. "I could see the whole bridge as it was going down," survivor says.

Doctors remove five small polyps from President Bush's colon. All were small, less than a centimeter [half an inch] in diameter. Bush reclaimed presidential power at 9:21 a.m. after about two hours. Vice President Dick Cheney assumed presidential power.

NEW: Atlanta Falcons owner Arthur Blank calls Vick's actions "incomprehensible" Vick agrees to plead guilty to one count of "Conspiracy to Travel in Interstate Commerce" Vick's admission that he was involved in the killing of dogs could lead to local charges. NFL Commissioner Roger Goodell suspends Vick without pay.

"I was so happy I didn't know what to do with myself," Youssif's mother says. "We just want to thank everyone who has come forward," his father says. The Children's Burn Foundation has agreed to pay for the family's travel to the U.S. "He will be getting the absolute best care that's available," foundation says.

Tomas Medina Caracas was a member of the high command of the FARC. U.S. officials say he helped manage the group's extensive cocaine trafficking network. He was indicted in the United States along with two other FARC commanders. FARC is Colombia's oldest, largest, most capable and best-equipped rebel group.

Rocket launcher tube found on front lawn of Jersey City, New Jersey, home. 20-year-old AT4 anti-tank rocket launcher tube is a one-time-use device. launcher has been turned over to U.S. Army officials at Fort Monmouth.

President Bush to tell Veterans of Foreign Wars that withdrawal from Vietnam emboldened terrorists. Bush: "The price of America's withdrawal was paid by millions of innocent citizens" White House billing speech as effort to "provide broader context" for Iraq progress report. President Bush has asked lawmakers to withhold judgment on troop "surge" in Iraq.

Police defuse a bomb consisting of 200 liters of fuel, gas cylinders and nails. A second car packed with gas and nails was later found to have been parked. Two weeks after the deadly 7/7 bombings, four men are alleged to have attempted to carry out a second wave of attacks.

Carlos Alberto joins Werder Bremen for a club record fee of $10.7 million. The 22-year-old scored in FC Porto's Champions League final victory in 2004. He is the third top Brazilian player to join the Bundesliga in three days.

Vice President Dick Cheney will serve as acting president briefly Saturday. President Bush is scheduled to have a routine colonoscopy at Camp David, Maryland. White House spokesman Tony Snow says no abnormalities were found in 2002 procedure. Snow himself is undergoing chemotherapy for cancer that began in his colon.

NEW: About 2,000 customers without power. Quake centered about two miles east-northeast of Oakland, at a depth of 3.6 miles. Oakland is just east of San Francisco, across San Francisco Bay. Quake set off alarms at people's homes.

NEW: President Bush: "A difficult decision was made to end the search" NEW: Labor Secretary Elaine Chao calls the ordeal "heartbreaking" The six miners have been trapped in a Utah coal mine for almost a month. Tests showed underground oxygen levels were too low to sustain human life.

At least 14 people killed, 60 others wounded in attack in Batna, east of Algiers. Bomb went off 15 minutes before expected arrival of President Abdel-Aziz Bouteflika. Algeria faces a continuing Islamic insurgency, according to the CIA. No immediate claim of responsibility.

Beckham has begun a five-year contract with the Los Angeles Galaxy team. CNN looks at how Bekham fulfilled his dream of playing for Manchester United. The road to major league football in the U.S. is a well-worn route for some of world's greatest players.

Virus found in healthy Australian honey bees may be playing a role in U.S. colony collapse. Colony collapse disorder has killed millions of bees, imperiling crops. Virus identified in the healthy Australian bees is Israeli Acute Paralysis Virus (IAPV) Although worker bees in colony collapse disorder vanish, bees infected with IAPV die.

Savers at leading UK mortgage bank line up for second day to empty accounts. Northern Rock was bailed out by the Bank of England after slashing profit forecasts. Shares in Northern Rock dropped up to 30 percent in Friday trading. British Bankers' Association has urged customers to "calm down."

NEW: O.J. Simpson will be held without bail after his arrest on robbery charges. NEW: Police say they have no information leading them to believe Simpson was carrying a firearm. Simpson is accused of directing several other men in an alleged armed robbery. Two firearms that police say were used were recovered early Sunday.

Nigeria's television survival show has been suspended after a contestant drowned. Anthony Ogadje, 25, and nine other contestants had gone to Shere Hills Lake. "Gulder Ultimate Search" sets a variety of physical challenges for participants. The winner was to get 5 million naira (about $39,000) in cash.

Roy Lynn Oakley, 67, of Roane County, Tennessee, appeared in federal court in Knoxville on Thursday. Oakley is a former employee of Bechtel Jacobs, the Department of Energy's prime environmental management contractor. Sources: Oakley was briefly detained for questioning in the case in January.

Chelsea are waiting on the fitness of John Terry ahead of Wednesday's Champions League match with Valencia. Center-back Terry suffered a broken cheekbone during Saturday's 0-0 draw with Fulham. Chelsea manager Avram Grant will see how he fares during training on Tuesday.

A dire shortage of donated organs in rich countries is sending foreigners to poorer places. Doctors in Pakistan have been arrested for abducting people, drugging them and stealing their kidneys. Donors in South Africa receive $700 for a kidney compared with $30,000 in the United States. China recently banned the sale of human organs and restricted transplants for foreigners.

Lohan fans have little to fear because no actor is uninsurable, say underwriting experts. Insurance rates for errant actors can range from 1 percent to 3 percent of a movie's production budget. "I don't think it (a problematic artist) is any more of an issue," expert says.

Francesco Totti has threatened to quit the Italian Players Association. Totti is unhappy with the starting date of the next Serie A season. The Italian Football League voted to start the season on August 26. Italy coach Roberto Donadoni wanted the first round of matches midway through the month.

Allegations that Blackwater USA was complicit in unlawful arms activities are baseless. Federal prosecutors are investigating allegations that employees of Blackwater illegally purchased weapons. U.S. attorney's office in Raleigh, North Carolina, is in the early stages of investigation. Blackwater resumed normal security operations in Iraq on Friday.

Youssif, the burned Iraqi boy, met his favorite superhero at Universal Studios. "It was my favorite thing," the boy said later. He met SpongeBob, Lassie and a 3-year-old orangutan. "Other than my wedding day, this is the happiest day of my life"

Cpl. Trent D. Thomas will be demoted to the rank of entry-level private. The 25-year-old was among seven Marines and a Navy medic charged in connection with the death. Thomas changed his plea from guilty to not guilty in February, arguing he had merely followed orders.

French foreign minister Bernard Kouchner has a reputation for challenging convention. He is a humanitarian as well as a patriot, with a strong commitment to human rights. He supported the US-led intervention in Iraq (while criticizing the aftermath) Washington will have been delighted by his warning to Teheran.

$2.3 billion was spent on political and issue-advocacy TV commercials in 2006. Costs to produce a TV commercial are no longer prohibitive for local and state candidates. Mitt Romney leads all candidates in TV spending, having aired his commercials more than 11,000 times. Romney is leading polls in the early voting states of Iowa and New Hampshire.

One-Two-Go jet crashed in bad weather as it landed at Phuket's airport on Sunday. Most of those killed were foreign nationals, and about 36 of the bodies still have yet to be identified. Of the 41 survivors who remain hospitalized, 38 are in stable condition and three in critical condition.

Filmmaker Michael Moore, CNN's Sanjay Gupta argue over "Sicko" Gupta: "I think it strikes at the irrefutable fact -- it's broken. We get it" Moore: "He said the facts were fudged. None of the facts are fudging"

India has elected its first female president, official results show. Pratibha Patil, 72, was the ruling coalition's nominee for the mainly ceremonial post. She easily beat opposition-backed challenger and vice president, Bhairon Singh Shekhawat. Patil supporters took to the streets, singing and dancing after the results.

Red Cross, UNHCR, UNICEF say most children were living with their families. Zoe's Ark said children were Sudanese orphans it was trying to rescue from war-torn nation. Three French journalists, seven-member Spanish flight crew and one Belgian arrested. Representatives of journalists, flight crew say they thought they were on humanitarian mission.

Explorer Dennis Schmitt found an island nearly two years ago near Greenland. Many climatologists and scientists say arctic ice melt is result of global warming. But others say it is simply the latest shift in the cyclical patterns of a planet's life. Most of the scientific community believes some warming is occurring.

Stacy Peterson, 23, has been missing from her suburban Chicago home since October 28. Judge signs order to exhume body of Drew Peterson's third wife, found drowned in bathtub. Drew Peterson initially told media he believed his wife ran off with another man. Investigators have twice searched the couple's home and vehicles.

Julia Vakulenko will face Lindsay Davenport in the final of the Bell Challenge. The Ukrainian will be seeking her first victory on the WTA Tour in Quebec. The 31-year-old American is seeking her second win in three tournaments since a baby.

Robert A. Singer, 49, is chief operating officer of the National Children's Museum. He is charged with five counts of distributing child pornography in interstate commerce. Some of the pornographic images were sent from Singer's computer at the museum. Museum: "We are horrified by the charges"

NEW: Court-appointed attorney says Chester Arthur Stiles is "a little out of it" NEW: Girl's mother says she is "relieved" about Stiles' arrest. NEW: She says she will testify against Stiles if the case goes to court. Stiles, 37, charged with 23 felony counts, including lewdness, sexual assault.

Dale Steyn takes career-best five for 34 as South Africa take tight grip on first test. New Zealand bowled out for 118 in reply to South Africa's 226 in Johannesburg. Hashim Amla and Jacques Kallis share an unbeaten stand of 159 as Proteas lead by 287.

Lazing in a hammock is one of the best ways to spend a summer evening. Running on the beach can get you into great shape. The best way to tie espadrilles is to cross and tie the laces once behind the ankle, then bring them forward and tie again.

Jordan is allowing all Iraqi children -- regardless of refugee status -- to enroll in schools. Even illegal refugees with no paperwork can send their kids to school. The move is cementing a massive population shift in the Middle East. More than 2.2 million Iraqis have fled the violence in their homeland.

NEW: Senate approves Michael Mukasey's nomination for attorney general by 53-40 vote. Nomination had been at risk because of questions about his views on waterboarding. U.S. and international law bans the technique, which produces the sensation of drowning. A majority of Americans consider waterboarding a form of torture.

Orme, Tennessee, relies on water trucked in from the next state. Mountain spring usually dries up at the end of summer, but just for a few days. This year it dried up early, on August 1, and hasn't revived. "When they cut it back on we jump for joy," Orme resident Debbie Cash said.

U.S. safety officials voluntarily recalled about 4.2 million toys Wednesday. Toys contain chemical that, once metabolized, converts into toxic "date rape" drug. Children who swallow the beads can become comatose, develop respiratory depression. Toys have also been distributed in Australia under the name "Bindeez Beads".

Tens of thousands of Congolese refugees flee camps as rebel troops attack government forces. Roads to Goma, about 10 miles from the camps, were crowded with refugees. Torrential rain made the movement even more difficult. U.N. says 375,000Congolese in North Kivu province have been forced from homes.

Web sites, blogs, bulletin boards preach the gospel of the grape in terms they can understand. Mission of wine sites like "Wine Library TV" is to demystify wine (and in some cases, sell it) Many of the new converts to wine are the under-30 age group.

Bangladesh Red Crescent fears death toll from Cyclone Sidr could be as high as 10,000. Thousands are still missing, while an estimated 280,000 others are unable to return to homes. Cyclone raked Bangladesh's southwest coast on Thursday with maximum sustained winds of 241 km/h.

Novak Djokovic crashes out of the Paris Masters after being beaten by Fabrice Santoro. The 34-year-old Frenchman won 6-3 6-2 in front of his home fans in Paris. World No. 3 has already qualified for the season-ending Masters Cup in Shanghai.

Lipstick outsold gloss by $76 million last year. Condition and protect with a balm that contains sunscreen. Choose a soft shade such as rose or nude that you can apply straight from the tube. Makeup artists use the same lipsticks again and again.

SPAM marks its 70th anniversary in 2007 which is also the Chinese Year of the Pig. National Museum of Funeral History features Civil War embalming display and replica of a turn-of-the-century casket factory. The Hobo Museum details history and culture of tramps.

Interpol makes global appeal for help to identify man from digitally reconstructed photos. Photos taken from the Internet show him sexually abusing underage boys. The man's face was disguised by digital alteration, but images could be restored. Interpol has determined photos were taken in Vietnam and Cambodia.

In 1851 Paul Julius Reuter opened an office in the City of London which transmitted stock market quotations between London and Paris. In 1865 Reuters was first in Europe with news of President Lincoln's assassination in the United States. Today Reuters has over 16,900 staff in over 94 countries.

NEW: Six of seven killed attended University of South Carolina. NEW: Six survivors are also USC students, university official says. One person described as "unaccounted for" was later confirmed dead. Mayor: "We suffered a terrible tragedy at Ocean Isle this morning"

Army Col. Don Farris: Attacks down 75 percent in recent months in northeastern Baghdad. Al Qaeda in Iraq presence has been "crushed" since beginning of May, he says. Iranian-backed Shiite militants still pose threat, Farris says. Despite improvements, "we still have a lot of work to do," he warns.

NEW: Santiago fire moves into Silverado Canyon, authorities say. Driver of white truck seen on Santiago Canyon Road on Sunday, near time fire started. $250,000 reward offered for information leading to arrest of person or persons responsible. Santiago fire, now 27,000 acres, was deliberately set, officials said Thursday.

The company was founded in 1985 by seven communications industry veterans. OmniTRACS is currently the largest satellite-based commercial mobile system. Qualcomm is among the members of the S&P 500 Index, Fortune 500. The company has been listed among Fortune's "100 Best Companies to work for"

NEW: "We have found the child, Madison. She's safe. The detectives say she is in good condition," sheriff says. Chester Arthur Stiles, 37, is being sought as a suspect, police say. Girl, now 7, was shown in a sex video made four years ago, detectives say.

AC Milan's Brazilian midfielder Kaka has been named European player of the year. The 25-year-old was a major factor in AC Milan's triumphant Champions League campaign. Manchester United's Portuguese winger Cristiano Ronaldo was runner-up. Barcelona's Argentinian midfielder Lionel Messi finishing third.

BUPA is an international health and care company with bases on three continents. BUPA's biggest and original business is health insurance in the UK. More than half of the UK's top companies are BUPA customers. The company's UK care homes offer specialist care to residents who include the elderly.

MI5 chief says at least 2,000 people in Britain pose a threat to security. Jonathan Evans says the figure only includes those the intelligence services know about. He says there had been 200 terrorist convictions in Britain since the 9/11 attacks. Evans says resources that could be devoted to counter-terrorism are instead used.

Ruben Navarrette: Immigration restrictionists like to pretend they're so high-minded. He says they always take the low road and harken back to the nativism that greeted earlier waves. Some fear that those who thrive in dominant culture are losing their primacy, he says.

Juventus earn 1-1 home draw with Serie A leaders Inter Milan on Sunday. Mauro Camoranesi scored with 13 minutes left to earn Juventus a point. Inter retain their unbeaten record this season, despite injury problems. Roma miss out on the chance to close the gap on Inter when a late collapse saw them throw away a two-goal lead.

Four Australian troops have now died in the conflict in Afghanistan. The incident occurred in Tarin Kowt in Uruzgan province. Taliban militants killed an Australian commando. The 26-year-old commando -- Pvt. Luke Worsley of Sydney.

France coach Raymond Domenech has omitted striker David Trezeguet from his squad. The 29-year-old has failed to win his way back into the 24-man party. France face the Moroccans on November 16 and then travel to the Ukraine on November 21.

Documents: Polygamist sect leader Warren Jeffs tried to hang himself earlier this year. Jeffs, leader and so-called prophet of 10,000-member Fundamentalist Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints. Documents: Jeffs confessed to "immorality" with a "sister" and a daughter more than 30 years ago.

Ferrari's Kimi Raikkonen wins Chinese Grand Prix to keep title hopes alive. Championship leader Lewis Hamilton spun out of the race to end his chances. McLaren team-mate Fernando Alonso finished second to move within seven points of Hamilton. Hamilton can still clinch the title with a third place in the final race in Brazil.

CNN will be hosting three events looking at modern strategies in today's business arena. Boardroom Master classes will take place in the homes of the world's largest stock markets. One of the guests at the event will be Howard Schultz, chairman of the international coffee shop chain Starbucks.

Sheikh Mohammed bin Isa Al Khalifa is the chief executive of the Economic Development Board. He is responsible for stimulating and supporting growth of the Bahraini economy. Sheikh Mohammed is concerned the nuclear dispute with Iran is deterring potential investors. He says Bahrain's strengths have been its human capital.

NEW: U.N. secretary-general condemns "abjectly cowardly strike" Two suspected car bombs strike Algiers within 10 minutes of each other. Algerian Interior Minister blames militant Islamic group with ties to al Qaeda. Al Qaeda Islamic Maghreb claims responsibility for attack.

Barcelona defeated big-spending Atletico Madrid 3-0 to stay in touch with Real Madrid. Barcelona had thumped Atletico 6-0 on their own ground last season and the visitors were out for revenge. It was Barcelona's fourth straight league win but they still trail Real Madrid by two points.

The Japan Grand Prix is to return to the Fuji Speedway, a circuit that hasn't seen an F1 race since 1977. The old Fuji Speedway was the setting for the 1982 arcade game Pole Position. Computer-aided design (CAD) is as much a part of the design of a circuit these days as it is of the cars.

Celtic have been fined $50,800 by UEFA and AC Milan's Dida has been banned for two matches. The incident saw a pitch-invading supporter approach the Brazilian goalkeeper. Celtic may choose not to complain about their own punishment, with half of their fine suspended for two years.

White House accuses Democrats of holding veterans care funding hostage. House passed health-labor-education bill last week with veterans funding attached. Senate later voted to strip out the veterans funding and send the bill to the president. President has threatened to veto the bill because of added spending.

Three University of Texas students emerge from cramped cave complex in Austin, Texas. The students were reported missing early Sunday after a trip into Airman's Cave. They were found about halfway down the 12,000-foot-long cave. Authorities do not know why the students were in the cave for so long.

U.S. first lady Laura Bush calls on Myanmar's military junta to "step aside" She says junta "should step aside to make way for a unified Burma" "The rest of the armed forces should not fear this transition," she says. U.N. Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon calls Bush to update her on efforts.

NEW: House panel chairman calls veto "not responsible and not credible" President Bush says $600 billion spending bill laden with $10 billion in "pork" Bill would have funded departments of Labor, Education, Health and Human Services. Bush also demands Congress reform the alternative minimum tax.

France lock Sebastien Chabal has been cited for a dangerous tackle on England's Simon Shaw. The Sale Sharks forward will face a disciplinary hearing on Monday. Chabal was brought on in the 26th minute to replace the injured Fabien Pelous. If he is suspended, then Chabal will miss Friday's third and fourth-place match.

Colorado man terrorized by threats after testifying against daughter's boyfriend. Witness says he has spent $10,000 on security system, hired bodyguard for son's wedding. No national statistics on crimes against witnesses exist, and minimal research has been conducted. Colorado has $50,000 allocated to its witness protection budget.

Previously unseen footage of Diana shown to jury at inquest into her death. Footage shows her smiling as she and Dodi Fayed step into elevator at Ritz Hotel. Further footage shows Fayed visiting a jeweler's shop. British coroner says it may never be known for certain whether Diana was pregnant.

Rudy Giuliani, Mitt Romney trade jabs over illegal immigration. Sen. John McCain, Rep. Ron Paul spar over Iraq war. Mike Huckabee says Internal Revenue Service should be abolished. Retired brigadier general asks candidates if military is professional enough to work with gay troops.

Maj. Gen. Doug Stone oversees U.S. detention centers in Iraq. He says detainees get free medical care equal to what he gets as a general. About one-third -- or 8,000 -- are in school, with 7,000 having passed the fifth-grade.

Tennessee Supreme Court refuses to modify or overturn lower court ruling. Mary Winkler convicted of killing her minister husband, Matthew Winkler. Winkler has not seen her three daughters in 15 months, her attorney says. The children have been living with their grandparents since their mother was arrested.

GEO-TV and ARY Digital offer a variety of programming, including news, entertainment. Both networks had been banned from Pakistan's cable television system. Pakistan's president, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, has been under pressure to lift a state of emergency. The action prevents the two Pakistani networks from broadcasting worldwide.

Nasser al Ansari is the CEO of Qatari Diar, a state-owned real estate investment company. The company is famous for its purchase of London's Chelsea Barracks. Al Ansari was at the office of the First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs as technical advisor.

42 people have been put to death this year, according to the Death Penalty Information Center. That figure is down 57 percent from what it was in 1999, when 98 inmates were executed. Texas continues to lead the nation, with 62 percent of executions nationwide this year. Overall, 86 percent this year were in the South.

Zenit Saint Petersburg clinch first Russian title in post-Soviet era with 1-0 win at Ramenskoye. Zenit finish top of the table with 61 points, two points ahead of second-placed Spartak Moscow. Nine-times champions Spartak beat city rivals Dynamo 2-1 in their final game.

Scottish Premier League leaders Celtic held 1-1 by managerless Hibernian. Gordon Strachan's team head the table by three points from Glasgow rivals Rangers. Inverness Caledonian Thistle follow up last weekend's shock 3-2 victory against Celtic. Third-placed Motherwell miss the chance to move above Rangers after being beaten.

Churchgoers in six states have held prayer sessions along the side of Interstate 35. Some believe I-35 is what is mentioned in the Bible as the "Highway of Holiness" A Texas minister says she received a revelation to start this campaign. Most people, the religious and the non-religious alike, don't buy any of this.

Venezuelan government places higher tax on alcohol and cigarettes. Alcohol now 10 percent more expensive; cigarettes are 20 percent pricier. President Hugo Chavez is on a campaign to make Venezuelans cut back on drinking. Stores near schools, churches and cultural centers will not be granted licenses to sell alcohol.

Two-thirds of adult Americans are overweight or obese, CDC says. Former President Clinton: "We need to do something about it for our children" CNN's Dr. Sanjay Gupta: "There's a battle going on, and we need to win the battle"

India's Yuvraj Singh smashes six sixes in one over as England lose by 18 runs. Singh becomes first player to do so in Twenty20 matches and fourth in all senior cricket. South Africa beat New Zealand by six wickets to keep semifinal hopes alive.

NEW: Chester Arthur Stiles to appear in court Friday, court official says. NEW: Authorities have not yet decided if Stiles will appear in person or via video link. Stiles, 37, was taken into custody Monday night after a Henderson, Nevada, police officer pulled over the white Buick Century he was driving. A former girlfriend of Stiles' said that, before the arrest, she lived in fear.

U.N. calls on NATO to do more to stop Afghan opium trade. Report shows export value of this year's poppy harvest stood at around $4 billion. Opium has accounted for more than half of Afghanistan's gross domestic product. 660 tons of heroin and morphine were trafficked out of the country in 2007.

David Nalbandian stuns world No. 1 Roger Federer in the Madrid Masters final. The Argentine, ranked 25th in the world, beat the Swiss star 1-6 6-3 6- 3. Federer was playing in his first tournament since winning the U.S. Open.

Juan Roman Riquelme scores twice as Argentina beat Bolivia 3-0 in World Cup qualifier. Midfielder follows up his brace of free-kicks in opening 2-0 victory against Chile. Argentina now five points clear of second-placed Brazil, who play Peru on Sunday.

Sen. Hillary Clinton calls troop withdrawal "too little, too late" Sen. John Edwards calls for immediate withdrawal of 40,000 to 50,000 troops. Sen. Christopher Dodd says it's useless to debate tactics when "the underlying policy is a complete failure" President Bush expected to endorse Gen. David Petraeus' troop withdrawal recommendations.

"Inspiring Impressionism" is organized by the Denver Art Museum. It opened Tuesday at the High Museum of Art, to run there through January 2008. With the backing of Northern Trust, the show will then travel to Denver February 23 to May 25, 2008. The Seattle Art Museum from June 19 to September 21, 2008, is host to pieces seen in Denver.

Serbian defender Nemanja Vidic will play for Manchester United against Dynamo Kiev. Vidic sat out Saturday's 4-1 victory at Aston Villa after suffering concussion. Louis Saha definitely misses the tie with a long-term knee problem. Glasgow Rangers without Jean-Claude Darcheville and Brahim Hemdani.

Pentagon preparing to set up new supply routes for troops in Iraq if Turkey cuts off U.S. access. Turkey incensed by resolution calling killing of Armenians by Ottoman Turks genocide. Turkey threatens to block access to Incirlik Air Base after resolution passed House committee. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi said she would bring measure to full House next month.

AC Milan goalkeeper Dida has had one game of his two-match ban suspended for a year. Brazilian Dida was also fined 60,000 Swiss francs by European football's ruling body. Dida will only serve the second match of his ban if he commits a similar offense in the next 12 months.

Lucky Dube, one of South Africa's most famous musicians, killed in attempted car-jacking. 43-year-old was killed in Johannesburg around 8 p.m. local time Thursday. His death casts a shadow over festivities ahead of rugby World Cup final.

"There was fear on their faces," passenger says of fellow passengers. Nationwide Airlines' Boeing 737 makes emergency landing in Cape Town, South Africa. Plane had only been in the air about 10 minutes before the engine fell. An object was sucked into the engine as the nose wheel lifted from the ground.

NEW: President Bush signs disaster declaration for seven California counties. FEMA director promises "a different type of response than the federal government put together" Katrina "was a wake-up call" and "this is a new FEMA," David Paulison says. FEMA and other relief services face significantly different challenges in California.

Vince McMahon: "Nothing from the WWE, under any set of circumstances had anything to do with Chris Benoit murdering his family" Critics say WWE pushes its stars and non-stars, works them too many nights per year. WWE drug screening program began in February 2006; 30 wrestlers have been suspended.

Justa Grata Honoria was Roman princess whose wild ways and naked ambition set off a chain reaction that culminated in the destruction of the Roman Empire. Smart, conniving, and ruthless, Honoria possessed all the attributes befitting a Roman emperor, except for that pesky Y chromosome. She seduced her brother's royal chamberlain and together, they plotted to murder Valentinian and seize power.

Football dignitaries gather in Sheffield, England, to celebrate Sheffield FC's 150th birthday. Guests of honor included Sepp Blatter, president of football world governing body FIFA. Inter Milan president Massimo Moratti scheduled to play friendly against Sheffield FC. Sheffield FC was instrumental in developing set rules for the game.

Ronaldinho has been recalled to the Barcelona squad for Tuesday's Champions League match against Rangers. The Brazilian was omitted from the squad that lost 3-1 to Villarreal on Saturday after returning late from international duty. Barca will be without Deco for that match though after the Portuguese suffered a thigh injury.

Teen rallies seek to "stage a reverse revolution" against secular popular culture. Teen Mania estimates it has reached more than 2 million teens with its message. Founder Ron Luce has waged a modern-day crusade against "purveyors of popular culture" Opponents point to Luce's views on homosexuality, abortion, religion.

After more than a decade of relative peace, the bombings and assassinations have returned. The conspiracies, the car bombs, the threatening rhetoric are eerily familiar. The cast in Lebanon's tragedy has changed little in two decades. The struggle where religion and clan play the main roles threatens to set Lebanon back.

Sallie Krawcheck is the Chairman and Chief Executive of Citi Global Wealth Management. Dubbed the "Mrs Clean" of Wall Street, she was credited with restoring investors' faith in analyst reports. She has made Fortune's list of the World's Most Powerful Women every year since 2002.

Santiago Fire started in two places along a little-traveled road, official says. Santiago Fire has burned more than 25,000 acres in Southern California. Reward for information leading to an arrest has increased to $250,000. L.A. Fire Department investigating whether suspect had role in other blazes.

NEW: Winds that gusted as much as 101 mph on Sunday drop to about 30 mph. NEW: Change in weather also means that firefighting aircraft can finally fly. Seven fires among 22 counted Wednesday were contained. About 500 homes lost in San Bernardino County east of Los Angeles.

NEW: Gillian Gibbons also faces deportation from Sudan after her prison term. Gibbons sentenced to 15 days in prison for allowing a teddy bear to be named "Mohammed" Gibbons, 54, was arrested Sunday after she asked her class of 7-year-olds to name the stuffed animal.

Ann Curley has been a type I diabetic for 40 years. She uses a pump attached to a catheter in her body to monitor glucose levels. The pump drips insulin into the body to keep blood sugars constant. Curley: Being diagnosed with diabetes forced our family to eat healthily.

Former Wales and British Lions center Ray Gravell has died of a suspected heart attack. Gravell had been on holiday with his family in the Spanish Mediterranean island of Mallorca. He won 23 caps for Wales and played on the Lions' tour of South Africa in 1980.

Sen. Barack Obama kicked off a series of local outreach gospel concerts. The concerts were meant to boost black voters' support for his presidential bid. When the campaign announced the lineups for the three-city "Embrace the Change!" gospel tour. Donnie McClurkin, a Grammy-award winning singer, is on record saying homosexuality is a choice.

Atletico Madrid crush European rivals Real Zaragoza 4-0 in the Primera Liga. Luis Garcia's first goal for the club, a double from Argentine Maxi Rodriguez and a Diego Forlan strike clinched a comfortable win. Valladolid continue to struggle in the top flight, crashing to a 2-1 defeat against Athletic Bilbao.

The company owns The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino and the Sands Expo and Convention Center. In May 2004, Las Vegas Sands opened the Sands Macau, located on China's southeastern coast. In December 2004, Dr. and Mr. Adelson rang the opening bell at the New York Stock Exchange.

Condoleezza Rice: "People need to serve where they are needed" Rice responding to objections to possibility of "directed assignments" in Iraq. Issue has caused an uproar in the State Department, resulting in a town hall-style meeting. If directed assignments are enforced, it will be the first time since the Vietnam War.

NEW: President Bush promises federal help for those affected by the fires. NEW: Cost of homes destroyed by the wildfires is likely to top $1 billion, official says. Four bodies believed to be illegal immigrants found in canyon east of San Diego. Twenty-three fires have scorched 472,478 acres, an area roughly three-quarters of the size of Rhode Island.

Cmdr. Michael B. Portland lost his post "due to a loss of confidence in his ability to command" Portland's demotion brings to 10 the number of people relieved of duty on the submarine. Six personnel have been punished for forging inspection records for the cooling system.

NEW: Bus driver Felix Tapia, 28, of Brownsville, Texas, and tractor-trailer driver David Rice, 45, suffered minor injuries. Two passengers were found dead inside the bus, said Arkansas State Police. Bus hopped a highway median and crashed into a pickup truck before being broadsided by an 18-wheeler.

Kelly Pless weighed 220 pounds at her heaviest. She lost 95 pounds through diet and exercise. Pless now runs 40 miles a week while she trains for two marathons. She's also set a new professional goal -- to pursue a doctorate in food and exercise psychology.

Singapore Airline-owned A380 completes maiden passenger journey between Singapore and Sydney. On board were nearly 500 passengers who had bid thousands of dollars for the historical experience. Singapore Airlines has ordered 19 superjumbos for an estimated price tag of $5.7 billion.

U.S. will tighten monitoring of export licenses, increase export restrictions. Officials plan to highlight two recent cases. F-14 components are widely sought by Iran, which is the only military in the world that still flies the jet. Representatives of more than a half dozen federal agencies will jointly announce plans.

Saudi Arabia is the UK's largest trading partner in the Middle East. The UK is the second largest foreign investor in the Kingdom. Exports to Britain are expected to reach a record high of $2.1 billion this year. Saudi Arabia is currently planning six privately-developed economic cities.

Tens of thousands of Congolese refugees flee camps as rebel troops attack government forces. Roads to Goma, about 10 miles from the camps, were crowded with refugees. Torrential rain made the movement even more difficult. U.N. says 375,000 people in North Kivu province forced from homes in past year.

Genarlow Wilson says he's glad he rejected a plea deal from prosecutors. Wilson, 21, served two years of a 10-year sentence for aggravated child molestation. Wilson was 17 when he had oral sex with a 15-year-old girl at a New Year's Eve party.

NEW: Two key Democratic senators say they will vote in favor of attorney general nominee. NEW: Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vermont, says he will vote against Michael Mukasey. Judiciary Committee is scheduled to vote on the nomination Tuesday. A number of Democratic senators have said they will oppose MukaseY.

At least 50 people were on the bus when it crashed on state Highway 163. Bus was traveling south from Telluride, Colorado, to Phoenix, Arizona. Bus lost control on a curve, ran off the road and rolled over several times. Most of the passengers were returning home from a weekend ski trip.

Naples has had problems in finding sites for municipal dumps. The region's dumps reached full capacity more than a decade ago. Since then a state of emergency has been declared every year. Government money: â¬1.8 billion in emergency funds devolved to deal with the problem.

14 strategic bombers take off from airfields across Russia on long-range missions. Putin: "We have decided to restore flights by Russian strategic aviation" U.S. President George W. Bush says he does not believe the flights pose a threat. Russian diplomats have clashed with the United States and European governments.

NEW: Britain also shuts its embassy in Baku to the public on Monday. The terror plot was unraveled after a weekend raid outside Baku. Several suspected members of the radical group were arrested. U.S. State Department spokesman says details "are still unfolding"

NEW: Two pirates killed, five captured, U.S. Navy says. Gunmen aboard two skiffs hijacked Panamanian-flagged Golden Nori over the weekend. North Korean crew regained control of Dai Hong Dan after pirates gave up weapons. Incident took place about 70 miles northeast of Somali capital, Mogadishu.

Suspect in fatal shooting of Philadelphia police officer captured in Miami. John Lewis, 6 feet, 270 pounds, was apprehended "unarmed and without incident," police say. Officer Chuck Cassidy was shot in the head when he inadvertently walked into a robbery. Cassidy was one of three Philadelphia police officers shot in a four-day period last week.

"Congress is not getting its work done," President Bush says. Bush: Senate "wasting valuable time" by taking up children's health insurance bill. House Majority Leader Steny Hoyer calls Bush "the biggest obstacle" to bill. Democrats quickly fire back, saying Bush's comments "ring hollow"

Sniper Lee Boyd Malvo says he is still "grappling with shame, guilt, remorse" Social worker: Malvo is a changed person since he and John Allen Muhammad terrorized Washington. Malvo, 22, spends 23 hours a day inside his cell at Virginia's toughest prison.

Italy coach Roberto Donadoni leaves Cristiano Lucarelli in his squad. The Shakhtar Donetsk striker scored twice against South Africa last month. Juventus striker Raffaele Palladino gets his first call-up to the senior squad. Italy go into the clash in Glasgow third in Group B.

UEFA has punished Benfica midfielder Augustin Binya with a six-match ban. The Cameroon international was sent off for a horror tackle on Celtic's Scott Brown. Brown avoided injury, but claimed BinyA had tried to break his leg. The 24-year-old can appeal against the ban.

NEW: Clinton's lead over Giuliani would be greater if a third-party candidate entered the race. Clinton leads Giuliani 51 percent to 45 percent in a head-to-head matchup. Clinton is the top choice of 44 percent of likely Democratic voters. Former Sen. John Edwards of North Carolina has 14 percent.

Vladimir Putin says Iran should be allowed to pursue nuclear program for peaceful purposes. Putin is in Tehran to attend a summit of Caspian Sea nations. Russia is building Iran's first nuclear power plant and has resisted U.S. sanctions. Iranian officials deny there was an assassination plot against Putin.

Three French journalists charged in alleged plot to kidnap African children arrive in Paris. French President Nicolas Sarkozy held emergency talks in Chad. 14 other people remained in custody in the African nation, some facing serious charges. Those who remain under arrest in Chad are six members of the French charity.

NEW: A sixth U.S. service member dies from injuries sustained in crash. Black Hawk helicopter crashed in northeastern Italy on Thursday. Four people were killed and seven were injured in the crash. The helicopter was an Army H-60 Black Hawk attached to 214th Aviation Regiment.

University of Memphis football player Taylor Bradford, 21, was shot last week. Three men have been charged with murder in perpetration of attempted aggravated robbery. Prosecutors are considering seeking the death penalty in the case. Bradford, a marketing major, was popular with the football team and campus.

Court orders pop singer Britney Spears to give up custody of her children. Kevin Federline is to retain custody of their two sons "until further order of the court" It was not clear what led to Monday's decision awarding Federline full custody. Last month, a judge ordered Spears to submit to random drug tests.

NEW: O.J. Simpson posts $250,000 bail. NEW: Judge orders Simpson to remain in jail until $37,500 is paid in full. Judge: "There's no 'get-out-of-jail-free card' today" Simpson faces trial April 7 on 12 criminal counts.

F-15s were grounded after a crash earlier this month in Missouri of an older model. Each F-15E must pass an inspection of critical parts on the airframe. The E-model aircraft is heavily used for ground support in the U.S.-led wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.

Two immigrants say they were injected with drugs against their will. One of the drugs in question is the potent anti-psychotic drug Haldol. Doctors say they are required to see patients in person before such drugs are administered. ICE says it doesn't respond to specific allegations due to pending litigation.

NEW: Mother did not know her daughter had ever been victimized, lawyer says. NEW: Mother recognized suspect, Chester Arthur Stiles, 37, a former animal trainer. Girl's videotaped rape set off a nationwide search last week. She was found Friday with family in Las Vegas.

Sen. Barack Obama says Sen. Hillary Clinton has shown "flawed" judgment. Clinton voted for resolution declaring Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps a terrorist group. Obama says he would have voted against the measure but was campaigning in New Hampshire. Clinton defends her vote on the resolution, saying it was a nonbinding resolution.

Bryant Purvis was facing charges of second-degree attempted murder and conspiracy. Charges have now been reduced against at least five of the students. Purvis says he has moved to another town to complete high school. Civil rights leaders Martin Luther King III and Al Sharpton led marchers to Jena.

Up to 1,000 human rights campaigners demonstrate in front of No. 10 Downing Street. Protesters call for resignation of Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf. Crowd includes Jemima Khan, ex-wife of former Pakistani cricket star Imran Khan. Imran Khan, who heads the Movement for Justice Party, was under house arrest.

NEW: T.I. will remain in custody until bond hearing Friday, federal magistrate says. NEW: Court room packed with family, supporters, media; more turned away because of overcrowding. Harris, 27, was arrested in a federal sting after his bodyguard-turned-informant delivered guns. Authorities say Harris provided the bodyguard $12,000 to buy the weapons.

Alleged leaders of counterfeit operations are three Chinese citizens living in New York. Authorities call it one of the largest counterfeit operations ever discovered. About 300,000 bags and wallets with names like Burberry, Gucci and Coach. They paid a total of about $16 million for what would have been more than $100 million.

National Hurricane Center director Bill Proenza leaves his position Monday. Nearly half of the NHC staff signed a petition calling for his ouster. Deputy Director Ed Rappaport has been temporarily placed in charge. Proenza caused an uproar last month with comments about a key hurricane satellite.

NEW: More than 1,700 dead in Bangladesh after tropical cyclone. Aid workers expect to find more bodies when remote villages are reached. Cyclone Sidr made landfall along western coast of Bangladesh near border with India. Thousands of people have been displaced and many are still missing.

R.E.M. song "Until the Day Is Done" debuts on CNN's "Anderson Cooper 360Â°" Song will also appear in CNN documentary "Planet in Peril" "We are honored to have our song included in this monumental project," singer Michael Stipe says.

U.S. government wants to build 700 miles of fence along the Mexican border. About 100 landowners are fighting it. Justice Department began legal action against those who have refused. Secretary of Homeland Security says fence will not be stopped by opponents like EloisaTamez.

Some Christian congregations are turning to the Church of Scientology for help. The church has long been in the headlines for practices critics say are little more than cult-like mind control. Two pastors say they are not scared off by programs with ties to a church that critics say has aggressive recruiting, secretive ways.

The attack occurred near an office housing judicial police in the city of Thenia. The blast destroyed about 20 houses, and a commission has been appointed to look after the victims. Islamic extremists in Algeria and other North African countries have struck several times. An al Qaeda affiliate claimed responsibility last year for the deadliest attack in Algiers.

Suspended NFL quarterback Michael Vick must adhere to tightened restrictions. Vick must participate in substance abuse therapy and mental health counseling. He must stay home between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m., "or as directed by the pretrial services officer" The conditions are to apply until Vick's sentencing, set for December 10.

Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr talk Beatles on CNN's "Larry King Live" "They were nothing," Starr says of his former bandmates. "We thought we'd be really big in Liverpool," McCartney says. Beatles' music used in Cirque du Soleil's "Love," which uses their music.

About 2,000 Palestinian refugees are stranded in camps along the Syrian border. U.N. agency has appealed for the resettlement of "vulnerable and sick" children. About 30 to 40 people arrive at the Al Waleed camp each week, UNHCR reports. Thousands of Palestinians have lived in Iraq, with some going there when Israel was formed.

U.S. Coast Guard searching for missing Japanese balloonist off Alaska coast. Friends of Michio Kanda last heard from him via satellite phone at 9 a.m. Thursday. Two Coast Guard C130 Hercules planes conducted searches Thursday. Kanda holds the world record for the longest-duration balloon flight.

Sens. Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama will duel for Super Tuesday votes. Event is the first Democratic debate since Obama's convincing victory Saturday in South Carolina. Former Sen. John Edwards suspended his presidential run Wednesday. Mike Gravel, the other Democratic presidential candidate, was not invited.

NEW: Condoleezza Rice says U.S. is outraged by the terrorist attack. NEW: Three Lebanese civilians killed, 21 others wounded in blast, security forces say. Car bomb explodes as it travels along a coastal highway north of Beirut. The driver of the embassy vehicle suffered minor injuries, State Department says.

Doctors in Britain taking legal advice to see if they are permitted to carry out hysterectomy. 15-year-old Katie Thorpe suffers from cerebral palsy. Charity says move could infringe human rights and set "disturbing precedent" Katie's mother says operation is in her daughter's best interests.

The number "eight" (ba) is considered auspicious by many in China because it sounds like the word for "wealth" and "fortune" Every year, many couples choose the 8th of August -- the eighth month of the year. Nearly 3,400 couples got hitched on the day last year.

Nihat Kahveci scores the only goal in Turkey's 1-0 win over Bosnia-Herzegovina. Turkey finish second in Group C behind defending champions Greece. Steffen Iversen scores a hat-trick as Norway beat Malta 4-1 in Group A.

Coalition troops kill al Qaeda emir of greater Samarra. Haitham Sabah al-Badri masterminded attack on Samarra's al-Askariya mosque. February 2006 attack set off violence and reprisal killings between Sunnis and Shiites. U.S. soldier sentenced to 110 years in confinement in rape of 14-year-old girl.

Richard Roberts steps down as president of Oral Roberts University. Three professors accused him and his wife of misconduct. Roberts and wife, Lindsay, have denied the allegations. Board of Regents to meet next week to discuss search process for new president."I want to see God's best for them," Roberts wrote in resignation letter.

Italian police arrest 20 people suspected of involvement in the recruitment of suicide bombers. Eleven of the arrests were in Italy, in the northern cities of Milan, Reggio Emilia, Bergamo, and San Remo. One was already in custody, so authorities served him with a new arrest warrant which included new charges.

NEW: Grand jury indicts four men in slaying of NFL star Sean Taylor. NEW: Eric Rivera Jr., 17, is alleged to have fired fatal shot. Taylor, 24, died a day after he was shot during an apparent burglary at his home. Taylor was regarded as one of the hardest-hitting players in the NFL.

NEW: Michael Mazza, 40, arrested outside a pawn shop in Hollywood, Florida. NEW: Mazza initially reluctant to talk to authorities, but later agreed, sheriff says. Deputy Paul Rein's death sparked a massive manhunt. Mazza is serving a life sentence for robbing a drugstore.

NEW: U.S. attorney opens criminal investigation into ship crash, oil spill. NEW: Coast Guard commandant says "human error factors" may have been involved. Coast Guard: Captain, crew barred from leaving ship, which is docked for repairs. Nearly 400 dead birds recovered from bay; 500 rescued alive but soaked in oil.

Almost 30 Josephs and Marys have signed up for the free night's stay at the Travelodge. The offer is good at any one of the chain's 322 hotels in the United Kingdom. The couples must bring proof of identity and must prove that they are in a long-term relationship.

NEW: U.S. Army recruiters turned down Robert Hawkins, 19, last summer, source says. NEW: Police seize computers, analyze information on Web sites in search of clues. Hawkins left a suicide note and other correspondence, police chief says. Police don't yet know why Hawkins chose mall or Von Maur department store.

Angelina Jolie: "There doesn't seem to be a real coherent plan to help them" Jolie is goodwill ambassador for U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. More than 4.2 million Iraqis have fled their homes, 2 million to neighboring states. Jolie has been working to help draw attention to the problem.

Udinese remain in fifth place in Italy's Serie A after suffering a 3-1 defeat away to Napoli. Ezequiel Lavezzi scored twice in two minutes to end a goal drought lasting two and a half months. Fabrizio Miccoli scored the only goal to give Palermo a 1-0 victory over Livorno.

A six-month trial has been launched at London's Heathrow airport using RFID. RFID tags will allow staff to more accurately track bags passing through the airport. The Â£150,000 trial will continue for six months tracking bags for passengers traveling with Emirates to and from Dubai.

Jordan's King Hussein sent secret message to President Nixon in 1970. Papers are among about 10,000 documents released by the Nixon Presidential Library. Documents detail U.S. efforts to persuade Saudi Arabia to move away from PLO. Nixon White House also adjusting to Israel's acquisition of nuclear weapon.

The Rev. James Orange died Saturday at Atlanta's Crawford Long Hospital. His 1965 jailing sparked a fatal protest that ultimately led to the Selma-to-Montgomery march. Orange was a project coordinator at the SCLC from 1965 to 1970. He is survived by his wife, five children and two grandchildren.

Voters in Beirut send pro-government candidate Mohammed al-Amin Itani to parliament. Itani replaces Walid Eido, who was killed in a June bombing. In Metn, a Maronite Christian suburb east of the capital, Camille Khouri upset former President Amin Gemayel.

Ex-CIA operative John Kiriakou talked about waterboarding of terrorism suspect. CIA asked the Justice Department to investigate whether he illegally disclosed classified information. Attorney says referral of case to Justice Department is standard procedure. About one case a week is referred to the Justice department, source says.

"The holiday's designed to make you feel (bad)," says Judy McGuire, author of "How Not to Date" If you're not dating anyone, take some time to indulge yourself. Make sure you're on the same page when it comes to Valentine's plans.

Majid Khan is being held at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. He is one of 14 "high-value" detainees held there. He alleges he was tortured while being held in secret CIA prisons. CIA spokesman: "The United States does not conduct or condone tortured"

NEW: Iranian mission to the U.N. calls the rejection "unfortunate" Ahmadinejad wanted to "pay his respects" and lay a wreath at the site. But workers are rebuilding the foundations of the site, police say. U.S. considers Iran a state sponsor of terrorism and accuses it of meddling.

Lisa Nowak is accused of stalking and using pepper spray against a romantic rival. Judge rules evidence found in her car and statements she made to police were inadmissible. Nowak, 44, is set to go on trial in April. If convicted, she would face up to life in prison.

Sharon Long is a forensic artist whose job is to help identify the dead. When Fort Myers, Florida, police found eight sets of human remains, they turned to her. Armed with sculptor's clay, glass eyes, wigs, Long creates a face from a human skull.

Four-week-old polar bear is being bottle-fed at Nuremberg City Zoo. Zookeepers took cub away from mother after fears she would eat it. Other female polar bear had eaten her two offspring, so zoo feared Vera would do the same.

Ron and Loretta Murray met with parents of victims of Colorado church shooting. Pastor Brady Boyd: "It made me evaluate my own life and think, 'Is there anyone I'm not forgiving?'" Matthew Murray, 24, killed two people and wounded two others in December 9 attack.

NEW: Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger asks U.S. Defense Secretary Robert Gates for help. More than 265,000 people have been evacuated and nearly 4,900 firefighters are battling blazes. 13 wildfires have consumed more than 98,000 acres and destroyed or damaged at least 50 homes. San Diego Zoo's Wild Animal Park closes.

Wednesday's Glasgow derby between Celtic and Rangers has been postponed. The postponement is a mark of respect following the death of Motherwell captain Phil O'Donnell. Motherwell's game against Hibernian on the same day was called off. Gretna's match against St Mirren was also postponed.

Long distances over questionable roads stop many Indians from making it into courtrooms. Mobile court is bused into rural areas to hear both criminal and civil complaints. With an estimated 300 million unresolved cases languishing in Indian courts, it could take more than 300 years to clear docket.

Chiquita Brands International faces $7.86 billion lawsuit on behalf of nearly 400 Colombian families. Plaintiffs are asking for $10 million in compensatory damages for each of the 393 victims. Chiquita, as part of a plea agreement, admitted that what it called protection payments. AUC was named a terrorist organization by the United States in 2002.

Police defuse a bomb consisting of 200 liters of fuel, gas cylinders and nails. A second car packed with gas and nails was later found to have been parked. Police say two vehicles clearly linked. July 7, 2005: Four suicide bombers detonate themselves aboard three underground trains.

NEW: Topps Meat Co. expands recall of ground beef from 300,000 pounds to 21.7 million pounds. NEW: 25 illnesses are under investigation in Connecticut, Florida, Indiana, Maine, New Jersey, New York, Ohio and Pennsylvania. The hamburger patties may be contaminated with E. coli O157:H7, company says. This is the company's first recall in its 65 years of business.

Buckweed Fire began October 21 in the Agua Dulce community. Sixty-three structures, 21 of them homes, were destroyed. The case will be presented to the Los Angeles County district attorney for possible charges. California Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger vowed to "hunt down" people responsible.

Sens. Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama in statistical dead heat in Texas. 50 percent of likely Democratic primary voters support Clinton, 48 percent back Obama. Many political strategists consider Texas and Ohio must-win states for Clinton. Arizona Sen. John McCain is clear favorite for Republican presidential nomination.

NEW: Fire chief: "I think it's a miracle that we haven't seen some serious injuries" Truck carrying 9,000 gallons of gas overturned and caught fire in Everett, Massachusetts. At least 200 people evacuated from their homes, including 84 residents of an apartment building.

Ricardo Izecson dos Santos Leite voted 2007 World Footballer of the Year by 96 journalists. Kaka won the award for his performance in the Champions League final. The 25-year-old Brazilian scored 10 goals as AC Milan won the Scudetto and the Super Cup.

Interpol makes global appeal for help to identify man from digitally reconstructed photos. Photos taken from the Internet show him sexually abusing underage boys. The man's face was disguised by digital alteration, but the images were capable of being restored. Interpol has determined the photos were taken in Vietnam and Cambodia.

Audit looked at management of presidential artifacts at six presidential libraries. Audit found "significant breakdown in internal controls" at the Reagan library. Ronald Reagan Foundation urges National Archives to move quickly to fix problems. Library has already begun implementing recommendations from audit, archivist says..

"I think it's a privilege to call yourself a Scientologist," Cruise says. Video was shown at a 2004 Scientology ceremony honoring Cruise for humanitarian work. Church of Scientology officials said it can be viewed at any of its churches. A pirated and edited version of the video appeared on YouTube this week.

Atlanta Falcons quarterback is scheduled to be sentenced on December 10. Vick is being held at Northern Neck Regional Jail in Warsaw, Virginia. Vick pleaded guilty in August after three associates admitted their roles in the operation. CNN Senior Legal Analyst Jeffrey Toobin speculated that Vick started his sentence early.

Pope Benedict XVI says football should be used to teach moral lessons. Italian football has been tarnished by corruption, match-fixing scandals and crowd trouble. The pope is reputedly a Bayern Munich supporter. In October, he was presented with a No. 16 shirt by Ancona club officials.

NEW: Bridge reopens after engineers inspect it, CNN affiliate reports. Four people killed in crash on bridge linking U.S. and Mexico. Three 18-wheelers and a minivan involved in the wreck appeared to have Mexican plates. 3.2-mile-long bridge connects Pharr, Texas, to the city of Reynosa, Mexico.

Rinko Kikuchi is one of Japan's hottest young actresses and models. She stunned global cinema audiences with her Oscar-nominated performance in "Babel" She recently worked with Karl Lagerfeld as the new face of Channel. Talk Asia follows her on a modelling assignment, discusses how her life has changed.

This month on Art of Life we feel the need for speed. Monita Rajpal meets the boys behind Ducati's motorbikes. Iron Maiden's Bruce Dickinson explains why flying is his new source of adrenaline. trance legend Paul Van Dyk takes us round his favorite haunt in the former East Berlin.

Michigan is a swing state, producing narrow margins of victory for presidential candidates. Top-tier Democratic candidates have taken their names off the ballot. The state's economy is powered by the automotive industry. Michigan's unemployment rate, 7.4 percent, is higher than the national average of 5 percent.

Lance Cpl. Maria Lauterbach could give birth at any time, sheriff says. Marine's car found at bus station, cell phone found at Camp Lejeune's front gate. Investigators say there was "suspicious activity" on her bank account. Facebook page: "Call mom!!! You know the number."

Coalition forces find 26 bodies buried in mass graves and a "torture complex" The complex was in an area thought to be an al Qaeda in Iraq haven. The bodies are believed to have been dead between six and eight months. Photos show chains hanging from walls and ceilings and a bed connected to electrical system.

U.N. nuclear watchdog chief says Pakistan's nuclear weapons could fall into hands of extremists. Mohamed ElBaradei's comments to Al-Hayat newspaper were "irresponsible" and "unwarranted" "Pakistan is a responsible nuclear weapon state," foreign ministry says.

Candidates express condolences, outrage over Benazir Bhutto's assassination. Candidates debate who is best qualified to deal with crises in other parts of the world. Hillary Clinton has spent a year calling herself the most experienced, most qualified candidate. Sen. Barack Obama's camp calls attention to Clinton's vote on the Iraq war.

After more than a decade of relative peace, the bombings and assassinations have returned. The conspiracies, the car bombs and threatening rhetoric are eerily familiar. The cast in Lebanon's tragedy has changed little in two decades. The struggle where religion and clan play the main roles threatens to set Lebanon back.

Seven Manchester United supporters taken to hospital after violence. British Embassy officials in Rome said five fans received stab wounds. Two others, including a 16-year-old boy, needed treatment for being drunk. None of the stab victims is understood to have serious injuries. Manchester United drew 1-1 with Roma in Champions' League tie.

Chester Arthur Stiles, 37, is a suspect in the videotaped rape of a 3-year-old girl. Stiles' former girlfriend says she believes she put him in contact with the girl. "I'm disgusted. I'm ashamed, embarrassed, mortified," Tina Allen says.

American al Qaeda member Adam Yahiye Gadahn renounces U.S. citizenship. Gadahn rips his passport in half and says, "Don't get too excited -- I don't need it to travel anyway" Gadahn speaks mostly in English, but references President Bush only in Arabic. The self-proclaimed American jihadist is on FBI's Most Wanted List.

Theodore Sorensen helped write John F. Kennedy's 1960 speech on Catholicism. He compared it to the speech on faith in politics delivered Thursday by Mitt Romney. Kennedy avoided discussing his religious views in the 1960 speech. Romney emphasized the role of religion in public life more strongly in his speech.

Boeing 777 has never been involved in a fatal accident during its service history. The aircraft seats between 301 and 368 passengers in a three-class configuration. Boeing prides itself on the 777's landing gear, which it claims is the largest ever incorporated into a commercial plane.

Donors pledge $7.4 billion to help build a Palestinian state, organizers say. Former British Prime Minister Tony Blair says donors need to be repaid. International Monetary Fund says it will monitor Palestinians' promised reforms. Palestinian Authority President Mahmoud Abbas earlier had requested $5.6 billion in aid.

NEW: Condoleezza Rice calls Rep. Tom Lantos "a true American hero" NEW: "He's going to be really, really missed," she says. NEW: He died at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Maryland. He was diagnosed with esophageal cancer in December.

Three car bombs in Amara kill at least 27 people, wound 151, officials say. Amara is provincial capital of Maysan province, scene of fighting between rival Shiite factions. Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki denounces attack, blames "Saddamists and Takfiris"

Tribal bonds remain stronger than national identity in Kenya. Country's 36 million people claim allegiance to around 40 different tribes. Last week's election pitched incumbent President Mwai Kibaki against opposition leader Raila Odinga. The result has been questioned by international election observers.

Saudi King Abdullah pardons rape victim sentenced to 200 lashes, six months in prison. Victim's husband: "This fatherly care and noble gesture will help (in) lifting the emotional and psychological stress and suffering" Case has drawn international attention, provoked outrage in the West.

Coroner trashes claims by Princess Diana's former butler. Paul Burrell said he knew a mysterious "secret" about the late princess. Coroner said the information was already in the public domain. Burrell's appearance was delayed after the coroner asked him to retrieve a letter.

President Bush chatted by phone with Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan. Iraqi President Jalal Talabani and Vice President Tariq al-Hashimi met with Kurdish Regional Government President Massoud Barzani. Iraqi Kurdish officials, while critical of the PKK, have denounced the Turkish bombing campaign.

Top-seed Andy Roddick beats Delray Beach winner Kei Nishikori of Japan 6-2 6-4. American number one needed just 63 minutes to defeat 18-year-old Japanese. John Isner beat third-seeded German Tommy Haas 4-6 7-6 6-3 to advance.

No one has been charged in the probe based on "credible allegations" from a former Marine. Marine volunteered information during employment polygraph test administered by Secret Service. Allegations first surfaced on a Web site, defendourmarines.com. Web posting includes account from a Marine who alleges eight captured Iraqis were gunned down.

Italian tennis players Potito Starace and Daniele Bracciali banned by ATP. Top player Starace suspended for six weeks and fined $30,000 for betting on matches. Italian Tennis Federation denounce the penalties as disproportionate. Concerns about match-fixing have risen since August.

Trevor Rees, formerly known as Trevor Rees-Jones, was front-seat passenger in the car. He sustained serious injuries in the August 31, 1997, crash. Rees says he received anonymous phone calls and letters after the accident. He has said the last thing he remembers that night was leaving the Ritz Hotel.

NEW: "I'm glad I'm home. Praise God," Frederick Dominguez says. NEW: Family used branches and sticks to spell out "Help" near culvert, pilot says. Family lost way while searching for Christmas tree in Paradise, California. More than 80 searchers scoured the woods.

"No Country for Old Men" wins best picture at 80th Academy Awards. Coens also win best director and best adapted screenplay. Four acting awards go to Europeans: Marion Cotillard, Daniel Day-Lewis, Javier Bardem. Swinton wins best supporting actress Oscar for her portrayal of Karen Crowder.

An American Airlines passenger complaining that she was having trouble breathing died on a flight last week. Flight attendants with sick passengers call Good Samaritan Hospital in Phoenix, Arizona. The top categories of in-flight illness are fainting, gastrointestinal problems, respiratory issues. By law, U.S.-based commercial airlines must carry automatic external defibrillators.

President Bush signs bill raising auto fuel economy standards for first time in decades. Bill also boosts federal support for alternative fuel research and energy conservation efforts. Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nevada, calls bill "a great, wonderful first step" House opponents such as Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, call bill "no-energy"

U.S. President George W. Bush stresses role of faith-based groups in fight against AIDS. Bush calls struggle one of conscience and morals on eve of World AIDS Day. More than 2 million people have died of AIDS this year -- including 330,000 children.

Oregon Supreme Court sends custody dispute back to trial court. Father converted to Judaism, told ex-wife he would convert as well. Mother objected, saying son had been raised in Russian Orthodox faith. Court: "Forcing M at age 12 to undergo circumcision against his will could seriously affect" relationship.

Two men were collecting crocodile eggs by a river bank in Australia's Northern Territory. A crocodile grabbed Jason Grant by the lower right arm, police said. The second man, Zac Fitzgerald, shot the crocodile, causing it to let go of Grant's arm. But a second shot that Fitzgerald fired struck Grant in the upper right arm.

Four active-duty U.S. soldiers charged with planning to rob drug traffickers. Rangers Carlos Lopez, David Ray White, Stefan Andre Champagne, Randy Spivey arrested. All four were to get a cut of the spoils of the robbery, affidavit says.

Nearly 3 million gallons of sewage spilled into San Francisco Bay when a pump failed. A pump failed at the South Marin Sanitation District's waste treatment facility. The waste was released into Richardson Bay, an inlet of the large bay. Boaters are being warned to avoid the Richardson Bay area.

Sixty-two members of Gambino, Genovese and Bonanno families face 80 charges. Charges range from money laundering to illegal gambling and murder. Four members of the Gambino family are charged with eight crimes involving murder. Arrests were made in New York City; Long Island, New York; New Jersey.

CBS: Hussein said he didn't anticipate U.S. would invade Iraq over WMD. Agent George Piro: Hussein wanted to be seen as "still the strong, defiant Saddam" Hussein asked his generals to hold off allied forces for two weeks, Piro says.

"We are mixed and we are many things," says Phillip Rodriguez, a documentary filmmaker. Latinos "very often don't share language," says Carl J. Kravetz, a longtime veteran of Hispanic marketing. "For me...there is no such thing as a Latino identity," says professor of Puerto Rican and Latino studies.

U.S. Navy moves guided-missile destroyer USS Cole to eastern Mediterranean. Deployment comes amid political standoff over Lebanon's presidency. Navy would not say whether the events are linked. The Cole was badly damaged by an al Qaeda bombing during a port call in Yemen.

Two-year-old Riley Ann Sawyers was beaten to death and her body was disposed of in Galveston Bay. Riley's body was found October 29 by a fisherman on an uninhabited island in the bay. Her identity was not known at first, and police dubbed her "Baby Grace"

Abdul Rahman al-Lahem says his license to practice has been reinstated. He represented a woman who was kidnapped and raped by seven men. She was sentenced to 200 lashes and six months in prison. The case attracted international attention and cast light on the treatment of women.

CNN is taking an in-depth look at contemporary Russia as part of the "Eye on Russia" series. We asked you to share your photos of Russia and tell us about your experiences in the country. Many of those who sent us photos were originally from other countries, like Justin Goney.

Italian news agency says al Qaeda No. 2 Ayman al-Zawahiri began planning killing. Such a claim has not appeared on radical Islamist Web sites. Source of the claim was apparently Italian news agency, Adnkronos International. One Islamist Web site repeated the claim, but that Web site is not considered reliable.

Sen. Jim Webb, D-Virginia, opened and then immediately gaveled the Senate session to a close. Nearly all the senators left the Capitol for the Christmas holiday last week. Democrats are keeping the Senate in session to block President Bush's recess appointments. Similar sessions were conducted over the Thanksgiving recess.

President Bush proposes temporary, broad-based tax relief package. Bush: Package must include "rapid income tax relief" for consumers. Existing income tax cuts supported by Bush administration are due to expire in 2010. Democratic leaders in Congress expressed general support for Bush's proposal.

More than 150 people have abandoned a sinking cruise liner that collided with an iceberg. The ship sent out a distress call at around 10 p.m. ET Thursday. Some 154 people are reported to be on board ship, which carries a Liberian flag. Passengers and crew have been evacuated onto lifeboats.

Todd Barber has dedicated his life to restoring the world's ocean reef ecosystems. He created a "Reef Ball" to mimic and rehabilitate all forms of oceanic reefs. Reef Balls are circular structures with a hollow center that serve as a base habitat. They can also help control erosion and stabilize shorelines.

Valerie Gooding is in the top five most powerful businesswomen in Europe. Under her leadership BUPA has grown to over 8 million customers in over 190 countries. Women often lack confidence to go for the next job, the top job, she says. Gooding: "I think men and women have very different styles of leadership"

NEW: Firefighters will remain at the hotel until "the fire is completely knocked out" NEW: Cause of the fire is unknown; Welders had been working on the roof. No one was trapped, and there were no reports of major injuries. The 32-floor building was completely evacuated.

NEW: Huckabee was trying to turn attention away from his foreign policy knowledge, aide says. NEW: Huckabee's tough immigration talk is also aimed at helping him win male GOP voters. Huckabee said 660 Pakistanis entered the country illegally last year. Huckabee is the GOP front-runner in Iowa, according to most polls.

NEW: Sen. Joe Biden says Bush's policies are "pushing us toward another Saigon moment" President Bush draws parallels between the cost of pulling out of Iraq and "the tragedy of Vietnam" Bush reiterates his support for Iraqi PM Nuri al-Maliki.

The U.S. Marshals Service is the nation's oldest law enforcement agency. Its Southeast task force arrested more than 3,000 suspects in 2007. The Atlanta office is equipped with a locker full of high-powered weaponry. They also have a high-tech operations center, complete with flat screen TVs.

Nguyen Thi Thanh, 41, convicted for "violating regulations protecting rare wild animals" She was arrested last September after police raided a house that she rented. Officers found dead tigers, bear arms, monkey bones and elephant tusks. She told police she sold the animals' bone marrow for $400 per gram.

CNN.com readers share memories of Heath Ledger, who was found dead Tuesday. Dena Michnowih says she came across Ledger in Brooklyn, New York, teaching his young daughter. Kristy O'Connor took a prenatal yoga class with Ledger and Michelle Williams.

Erik Prince: "There was definitely incoming small arms fire from insurgents" He says there was no "deliberate violence," committed by Blackwater employees. Prince says he expects the FBI investigation to provide many answers. Iraqi government accuses Blackwater guards of opening fire on civilians.

Victor Okumu, 51, a Kenyan doctor; Damien Lehalle, 27, a French logistician; and a Somali driver named Billan were the MSF workers. Also killed was journalist Hassan Kafi Hared, 36. Remote-controlled mine erupted as he was walking to a news conference in northern Kismayu.

Tim Masters spent nine years in prison for the murder of Peggy Hettrick. On Tuesday, a judge threw out Masters' 1999 murder conviction. On Friday, a prosecutor asked a judge to dismiss the first-degree murder charge. The prosecutor did not rule out future prosecution.

Jamie Lynn Spears, 16, says she's pregnant and the father is her 18-year-old boyfriend. There has been no public talk of criminal prosecution in the case. Consensual sex between the two may well have been legal, depending on where and when it took place. Critics of the nation's statutory rape laws say laws are ignored in some cases.

Indian police accused of covering up murder of British teenager in Goa. Scarlett Keeling, 15, was found dead on Anjuna beach last month. A second autopsy suggested she had been raped and murdered. Police say they are investigating allegations of a cover-up and the actions of junior officers.

Victor Okumu, 51, a Kenyan doctor; Damien Lehalle, 27, a French logistician; and a Somali driver named Billan killed. Also killed was journalist Hassan Kafi Hared, 36. Remote-controlled mine erupted as he was walking to a news conference in northern Kismayu.

Ricardo Izecson dos Santos Leite voted 2007 World Footballer of the Year by 96 journalists. Kaka won the award for his performance in the Champions League final. The 25-year-old Brazilian scored 10 goals as AC Milan won the Scudetto and the Super Cup.

Marine Cpl. Cesar Laurean is charged with first-degree murder. He remains at large, and authorities say he may have fled to Mexico. Affidavit: Christina Laurean knew about death one day before reporting it to authorities. Laurean, a naturalized U.S. citizen, has mailed at least one letter from Texas.

NEW: Clinton: "If your whole candidacy is about words, then they should be your own words" NEW: Obama: "Deval and I do trade ideas all the time, and you know he's occasionally used lines of mine" Obama says he also used some of Deval Patrick's words at a Jefferson-Jackson dinner. Clinton campaign points to similarities between Obama and Patrick's speeches.

NEW: Four dead adults were shot, two dead children were stabbed, sources say. NEW: Three other children who were wounded in the home were taken to a hospital. Police found six people -- two men, two women and two boys -- dead in a home. Neighbor says he heard gunshots coming from the house Saturday night.

Four men arrested in connection with shooting death of NFL player Sean Taylor. Police have more than one confession in the case and the individuals will be charged with murder. Taylor, 24, died Tuesday, a day after he was shot during an apparent burglary at his Miami home.
