Rizana Nafeek was 17 when she started work in Saudi Arabia. She was convicted of killing a 4-month-old baby boy in her care. Her father says the child died accidentally, choking on milk. Rights groups say case highlights vulnerability of Sri Lankans who work abroad.

Atlanta Falcons quarterback Michael Vick is expected to plead guilty to federal conspiracy charges. CNN.com readers weigh in on whether they think Vick should be allowed back on the field. "How can we allow someone like that to be a role model for children?" asks one reader.

Billionaire Richard Branson left school at 16 to start his own record company. Branson now owns more than 300 companies, from cola to trains. He says the Virgin brand is "absolutely paramount" for his key lieutenants. "I see my life as one long university education I never had," says Branson.

NEW: Police believe child they dubbed "Baby Grace" is actually 2-year-old Riley Ann Sawyers. NEW: DNA analysis is still in progress to confirm that identification. Mother, boyfriend arrested Saturday on charges of injuring a child and tampering with evidence. Fisherman discovered the body in a blue Sterilite plastic container on an uninhabited island.

NEW: Eric Rivera Jr., 17, charged as an adult with first-degree felony murder. NEW: Three other suspects appear in court via videoconference. Four men indicted on murder, burglary charges in slaying of Sean Taylor. Taylor, 24, died a day after he was shot during an apparent burglary at his home.

Football will pay tribute to Manchester United's Busby Babes on the 50th anniversary of the Munich air disaster. Eight players lost their lives on February 6, 1958, when Flight 609 ZU crashed on the third attempt to take off after re-fuelling in Germany.

Presidents of Sudan and Chad sign a non-aggression agreement late Thursday. Agreement aims to halt cross-border hostilities between the two African nations. Each country accuses the other of supporting armed rebel groups. U.N. says refugees and armed groups regularly crossing border between Sudan, Chad.

Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, wants appeals court to overturn judge's decision. Judge refused to let Craig withdraw a guilty plea to misdemeanor charges. Craig entered guilty plea after his arrest in a men's room at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport. Craig has denied he is gay.

Queen Elizabeth opens Heathrow's $8.6 billion new Terminal 5 on Friday. The first flights from the new terminal are scheduled for March 27. It is part of a strategy which could lead to passenger numbers almost doubling to 122 million. Environmental groups have voiced concerns over the expansion.

Condoleezza Rice: No U.S. citizen or private organization will be allowed to engage in financial transactions. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson: "Iran funnels hundreds of millions of dollars each year through the international financial system" The move marks the first time the United States has attempted to punish another country's military through sanctions.

Sheikha Lubna Al Qasimi is the first woman to hold a ministerial post in the United Arab Emirates. In 2000, she founded Tejari, the first Middle Eastern business-to-business marketplace. 70 percent of Dubai's government purchases are made online, she says.

NEW: New York Times: Spitzer paid $4,300 for 2Â½ hours with a call girl he arranged to meet. Spitzer announced his resignation Wednesday, two days after reports of his connection. He has not been charged with a crime. The investigation began when New York's North Fork Bank notified Treasury Department.

Myanmar's pro-democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi "ready to cooperate" U.N. special envoy Ibrahim Gambari says she is committed to pursuing dialogue. Gambari met with Myanmar's prime minister, Gen. Thein Sein, and other government officials. Aung Kyi was appointed as liaison officer amid international pressure following crackdown.

Pakistan election officials disqualify opposition party leader Nawaz Sharif. Sharif was convicted of terrorism, hijacking and tax evasion in 1999. He was released in 2000 in exchange for agreeing to 10 years of exile in Saudi Arabia. He returned to Pakistan last month after seven years in exile.

AC Milan's Brazilian midfielder Kaka has been named European player of the year. The 25-year-old was a major factor in AC Milan's triumphant Champions League campaign. Manchester United's Portuguese winger Cristiano Ronaldo was runner-up. Barcelona's Argentinian midfielder Lionel Messi finished third.

European leaders agree to send 1,800-strong security force to Kosovo. Kosovo is expected to declare independence from Serbia early in the new year. Serbia insists the region should remain autonomous within its borders. European leaders trying to balance readiness to back Kosovan independence with incentives.

Tocopilla, Chile, north of Santiago, is about 35 km (21 miles) from the quake's epicenter. "There are more than a thousand, 1,200 houses, at least, that were totally flattened," mayor says. Quake collapsed a roadway tunnel, temporarily trapping about 50 construction workers.

"There is no evidence of intent on the part of the minor," prosecutors say. The boy had faced possible charges in juvenile court. The fire started October 21 in the Agua Dulce community north of Los Angeles. It was one of nearly two dozen wind-whipped wildfires in southern California.

NEW: Police find "trace of violent activity in the house," sheriff says. Lance Cpl. Maria Lauterbach, 20, reported missing from Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, December 19. Suspect Cesar Armando Laurean is the suspected killer, and is being sought. Authorities searching Laurean's home found a cavity in his backyard earlier Friday.

Investigators smuggled bomb-making components into U.S. airports, GAO says. GAO: Investigators took advantage of "weaknesses in TSA procedures and other vulnerabilities" GAO recommends special screening lines based on risk and passengers with special needs. TSA chief defends administration's policies and procedures, says they are effective.

Fantasy author Terry Pratchett has been diagnosed with a rare form of Alzheimer's. The 59-year-old says he plans to continue writing his multi-million selling Discworld books. His books have, according to his Web site, sold more than 45 million copies worldwide in 33 languages.

Iraqi forces detain suspected leader of a terrorist cell network. Cell believed to be funded by Saddam Hussein's eldest daughter. Raghad Hussein is wanted by Iraqi authorities on terrorism charges. She has been living in Jordan under the protection of the royal family. The raid happened Sunday in Hussein's hometown of Tikrit.

Sen. Hillary Clinton's eyes welled with tears as she spoke in New Hampshire. Clinton: "I couldn't do it if I just didn't, you know, passionately believe it was the right thing to do" "This is very personal for me, it's not just political," she says.

Amnesty: "A climate of impunity has prevailed, the economy is in tatters" Red Cross: "Despite limited improvements in security in some areas, armed violence is still having a disastrous impact" Both reports slam the Iraqi government for failing to grapple with the critical needs.

Festival del Sole in Napa Valley, California, has just concluded its second year. Organizer Barrett Wissman: "It's a mission in my life to have more and more people enjoy and love the arts" IMG Artists' roster includes violinists Joshua Bell and Itzhak Perlman.

Lyon stay four points clear at the top of the French league with a 2-0 win over Valenciennes. Goals from Juninho and Sidney Govou give the six-time champions the win. Nancy celebrate their 40th anniversary with a 1-0 victory over Girondins Bordeaux.

Sen. Hillary Clinton wins New Hampshire primary with 39 percent of vote to Sen. Barack Obama's 37 percent. Clinton ahead of Obama 45 percent to 34 percent among those who said they were registered Democrats. Clinton claimed majority of women's votes, in contrast to last week's Iowa caucuses.

U.N. Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon is "urgently dispatching" a special envoy to Myanmar. The envoy, Ibrahim Gambari, is scheduled to lead a briefing on the situation in Myanmar. Protests at the crackdown have taken place overseas, including one outside the Myanmar embassy.

Single-sex service is available on four major lines in Mexico City. One woman described the service as "excellent," saying it's "more comfortable" Last year, the government received seven complaints of sexual abuse aboard the city's buses. Authorities said that a single complaint is enough to justify such measures.

Kuwait's leader dissolved parliament on Wednesday and called for early elections. Cabinet resigned this week following a power struggle with the government. Sheikh Sabah al-Ahmad al-Sabah said he was forced to dissolve parliament. New elections have been set for May 17, according to state-run news agency.

NEW: Bodies found in wooded area of Columbus, Georgia, FBI says. NEW: A coroner will confirm the identities of Eddie Harrington and his three children. Harrington, 28, took the children March 5, police said. Harrington sent a letter indicating his intent to kill the children, police say.

Keri Christensen is among the first women in the U.S. to be classified as combat veterans. Women have made up about 11 percent of the military force in Iraq and Afghanistan. In 2007, the VA diagnosed 60,000 veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder. 22 percent of women suffered from "military sexual trauma," VA found.

More than 500,000 women worldwide die each year as a result of childbirth complications. Nearly 7 million babies are either born dead or die within 28 days of their life. One H.E.A.R.T. provides childbirth education and equipment to those in need.

Bodies of Chandrasekhar Reddy Komma and Kiran Kumar Allam found in apartment. No suspects identified in what police are investigating as a double homicide. Neighbors told police three strange men were seen in the area. Emergency text messages were sent to students and faculty across the LSU campus.

NEW: Arrests reinforce fears in Europe that radical Islam is trying to suppress free speech. NEW: Newspaper editor: "The arrests have hopefully thwarted the murder plans" Danish citizen is charged with a terrorism offense, the intelligence service says. The operation took place in the Aarhus area of western Denmark.

South Africa, Argentina, Thailand, Brazil, Costa Rica, India and Singapore have become major players. Cosmetic, or elective, procedures aren't covered by insurance, so cost is motivating factor. International Society of Aesthetic Plastic Surgery warns against low-cost surgery. Some medical professionals fear patients will overlook severity of invasive surgeries.

Fossilized remains of a giant rodent have been found in Uruguay. The 3-meter-long creature weighed 1,000 kilograms and was 1.5 meters tall. Scientists believe it lived about four million years ago in South America. The largest living rodent is a 50 kilogram guinea pig found in the region.

Atlanta topped Los Angeles in reporting the most bank heists, FBI says. FBI says violent crime is up across the nation, especially in major metro areas like Atlanta. Atlanta's rapid growth over the last decade has also been a factor. Atlanta has 26 more banks than in all of North Carolina.

"I am not the bad person or the beast I've been made out to be," Michael Vick writes. Vick was sentenced to 23 months in prison for financing a dogfighting ring. Other letters supporting Vick were sent by his mother, his seventh-grade teacher and children.

Steven Spielberg found stolen Norman Rockwell painting in his collection. Recovering masterpieces happens in less than 5 percent of cases, FBI says. Art thieves do a simple risk versus reward evaluation, expert says. On Sunday, robbers made off with four paintings worth an estimated $163 million.

Pete Sampras beats current world number one Roger Federer 7-6 6-4 in Macau. Federer had one the two previous clashes in an Asian series in straight sets. American ace Sampras downplayed his victory, noting Federer was coming off a long season.

Alex Trebek, 67, has hosted "Jeopardy!" for 23 years. Trebek suffered a minor heart attack at his home Monday night. He is recovering at a local hospital, and it is not clear when he will be released. He has hosted a number of game shows, including "High Rollers"

Archaeologists find what they think are ruins of an Aztec pyramid in Mexico City. Construction workers unearthed ancient walls in Iztapalapa neighborhood in June. Government archeologists believe they may be part of the main pyramid of the Aztec city. The main pyramid was destroyed by conquistador Hernan Cortes in the 16th century.

Two men, 36 and 18, sentenced to 15 years in prison for rape of 15-year-old French boy. The boy's mother, Veronique Robert, promised to appeal the sentence. Robert believes crime is tantamount to attempted murder because attacker was HIV-positive. Dubai government spokesman says sentence is not lenient.

Chile and Peru have bickered over the rich Pacific coast fishing waters for years. Peru published a new map on Sunday that pushes its bid to negotiate a new sea border. Chile's government protested the move and said it was calling home its ambassador. Peruvian President Alan Garcia said in June his country would take Chile to the International Court.

President Bush says bill "moves our country's health care system in the wrong direction" Bill would have expanded State Children's Health Insurance Program by nearly $35 billion. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi calls for a January 23 vote on whether to override the veto. SCHIP covers about 6 million children whose parents earn too much to qualify for Medicaid.

U.S. radar picked up the Russian turbo-prop Tupolev-95 planes about 500 miles off the Alaska coast. U.S fighters from Elmendorf Air Force Base were dispatched to meet the bombers. The United States maintains the air exclusion zone off the coast of Alaska.

NEW: Bill Clinton says Oprah Winfrey has "the best combination of mind and heart" NEW: Winfrey praises Obama's "ear for eloquence and tongue for unvarnished truth" Obama campaign officials estimate more than 30,000 people in South Carolina. South Carolina is one of the first states to hold its presidential primary.

Debra Lafave arrested for "inappropriate but non-sexual contact" with coworker. Lafave, 27, pleaded guilty in November 2005 to having sex with a 14-year-old boy. She was sentenced to three years under house arrest and seven years of probation. "I can only characterize this as somewhat of a bizarre and unusual violation"

Delta cancellations will affect flights up until early Friday. American Airlines cancels 132 of its estimated 2,300 flights scheduled for Thursday. The cancellations forced dozens of people to spend the night in the atrium of Atlanta's airport. This latest round of inspections was prompted by questions raised by the FAA and American safety officials.

NEW: Four crew members confirmed dead, one still missing, Coast Guard says. NEW: Company identifies dead as Captain Eric Peter Jacobsen, Chief Engineer Daniel Cook, Mate David Silveira and Crewman Byron Carrillo. Vessel reported water was leaking into steering gear compartment about 2:50 a.m. Sunday. The 180-foot processing trawler was about 120 miles west of Dutch Harbor.

CNN Student News: Gadget Gifts and Tech in the Classroom. A college professor finds a way for his students to listen to his lectures even when they're not in the classroom. We talk to students and experts to find out some of the ways technology is being used in schools.

NEW: U.N. secretary-general condemns "abjectly cowardly strike" Two suspected car bombs strike Algiers within 10 minutes of each other. Algerian Interior Minister blames a militant Islamic group with ties to al Qaeda. Al Qaeda Islamic Maghreb claims responsibility for the attacks.

Four people accused of setting fire to Michigan State University building in 1999. Fire caused more than $1 million in damage to facilities, loss of research records. Michigan State Police Chief James Dunlap calls case "significant act of domestic terrorism" "It was an assault on the core value of free and open inquiry at a research university"

Kevin Brown, a Jamaican national, caught the attention of an air safety officer. Brown was arrested on charges of carrying a weapon or explosives onto a plane. "He looked rather crazy," a passenger told CNN affiliate WKMG. Brown is scheduled for an initial appearance in federal court on Wednesday.

A380 superjumbo bound for Sydney comes loose from a tow truck and rolls onto grass. No-one injured in incident involving the world's biggest airliner. Singapore Airlines was the first carrier in the world to operate the double-decker aircraft. Most passengers departed for Sydney on a new flight early Friday morning.

NEW: Dalai Lama says he does not seek the separation of Tibet. NEW: He says he has no desire to "sabotage" the Olympic games. China has blamed followers of the Dalai Lama for instigating the unrest. President Bush said Friday he "urged restraint" during a phone conversation.

The gray wolf was removed from the Endangered Species Act's "threatened" list. The decision has stoked controversy among environmentalists and ranchers. The wolves were eliminated from Yellowstone decades ago before being reintroduced. There are now more than 1,500 wolves across Wyoming, Idaho and Montana.

NEW: House votes 227-183 to give concurrence to the bill. NEW: House Minority Leader John Boehner: "America will be the safer for it" Measure would temporarily expand government's power to conduct electronic surveillance. Measure would authorize NSA to intercept communications between U.S. and foreign targets.

Cuba's government believes its citizens are not working hard enough. Salaries average about $15 per month on the island, and Cubans get monthly food rations. The black market is so widespread that Cubans have coined a special term for breaking the law. Raul Castro has said the country must become more productive.

A team found the gold necklace near Lake Titicaca in Peru. It's 4,000 years old -- 600 years older than any other gold jewelry discovered in the Western Hemisphere. Find is important because it signals the early emergence of a desire for status among people who lived as relative equals without a formal leadership system.

Bolivian President Evo Morales plans to sign legislation scheduling referendum. The proposed constitution would strengthen the country's indigenous majority. It has faced fierce opposition from nonindigenous Bolivians. Congress made its decision to hold a referendum "with a reduced presence of opposition lawmakers"

B-2 stealth bomber crashes early Saturday morning local time in Guam. Two pilots ejected from the bomber and were in good condition afterward. Crash is the second in three days of an Air Force craft. On Wednesday, two F-15C jets collided during a training exercise.

Paint sealant, fabric protection/leather care, extended warranties, rust/underbody coatings, anti-theft systems. Some of these extras have real value and are probably worth adding. If you eat in your car, consider fabric or leather protections.

Jeff Donohoo, 36, is a cafeteria worker at a hospital in Chattanooga, Tennessee. He was diagnosed with autism when he was in his freshman year of high school. "Jeff has a social problem, not a mental problem," his mother says. Today, interacting with people is easier for him than it once was.

A Chinese couple tried to name their baby "@," claiming the character echoed their love for the child. Chinese has no alphabet and instead uses tens of thousands of multi-stroke characters. Earlier this year the government announced a ban on names using Arabic numerals, foreign languages and symbols.

Miami ranks as the worst city for most aggressive drivers for the second straight year. AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety studied more than 10,000 incidents of road rage. At least 218 people were killed and another 12,610 injured when drivers got angry. AAA offers a three-step plan to avoid becoming a victim of aggressive driving.

Courtney Larrell Lockhart's mother says she's sorry for victim's family's suffering. Lockhart, 23, is charged with capital murder, robbery, kidnapping, attempted rape. Lauren Burk, 18, of Marietta, Georgia, was found shot Tuesday night near campus. Memorial services for Burk were held Saturday and Sunday.

Former cave-dweller claims two women died and were buried inside. Vitaly Nedogon relayed his claims to Russian TV journalists. Officials believe 11 people are left in the cave, but only nine will be alive. The cave ordeal began when the group's leader told followers to hide themselves.

Refugees International says U.S., Iraq not doing enough to help internally displaced. Social services being provided by "militias of all denominations" that want to build groups. Muqtada al-Sadr's political movement using Hezbollah model to set itself up.

Iowa is one of the most evenly divided states in the nation. The central part of the state is Iowa's most Democratic area. Western Iowa, on the other hand, is home to the most Republicans. The support of Iowa's largest newspaper may also play a role in Thursday's caucuses.

Ajax lost ground on Dutch league leaders PSV Eindhoven after being held to a 2-2 draw. Heracles registered their first away win of the season with a 5-0 thumping of Venlo. Relegation-threatened Sparta Rotterdam and NEC Nijmegen both won.

Queen Elizabeth opens Heathrow's $8.6 billion new Terminal 5 on Friday. The first flights from the new terminal are scheduled for March 27. It is part of a strategy which could lead to passenger numbers almost doubling to 122 million. Environmental groups have opposed the expansion of Heathrow Airport.

Coca Cola was born in Atlanta, Georgia, on May 8, 1886. The Coca-Cola Company is the world's largest beverage company. The company currently has over 400 different brands under its control. It employs approximately 71,000 people, including 58,000 in Africa.

Soyuz capsule carrying South Korea's first astronaut lands in northern Kazakhstan. Crew subjected to severe G-forces during the re-entry, officials say. Search helicopters took 25 minutes to find the capsule and determine that the crew was unharmed. In October, the Soyuz capsule landed 70 kilometers from the planned area.

NEW: "I think God was holding my ass, teaching me that I hadn't been doing everything he wanted me to do," survivor says. James Kruger survived after Tuesday night's storm blew his house away above him. Pam Whitaker lost her home and everything in it, including the money from cashing her disability check. The trail of death stretched across four states, with four fatalities in Alabama.

Antonio Nararainsami, 36, died after falling four stories at Shea Stadium. Police say he was sitting on the banister of the escalator when he lost his balance. His daughter, Emily, says her father was not sliding on its banister when he fell.

Heather Mills awarded Â£24.3 million, far less than the Â£125 million she had sought. Mills represented herself and was a "less than impressive witness," judge says. Mills lost her left leg below the knee in a 1993 traffic accident. Judge discounted many of Mills' arguments about personal wealth before and after marriage.

Roger Bergendorff, 57, taken into custody Wednesday morning in Las Vegas, Nevada. He was hospitalized with what was diagnosed as ricin exposure in February. Ricin is a poison that can be made from the waste of castor bean processing. If convicted of all charges, he faces a maximum penalty of 30 years in prison.

Author says he plagiarized or made up portions of Lonely Planet guidebooks. Thomas Kohnstamm also claims he accepted free travel, violation of company policy. Lonely Planet publishes more than 500 titles and employs 300 authors. Publisher says "urgent" review of books did not reveal any inaccuracies.

Samsung Group chairman Lee Kun-hee plans to resign, Yonhap reports. Lee was indicted for tax evasion and breach of trust. Samsung is South Korea's largest conglomerate. It has annual sales of nearly $160 billion and accounts for 18 percent of S.Korea's output.

Indonesian court sentences alleged military commander of al Qaeda-linked terror network. Abu Dujana is accused of direct involvement in Bali nightclub bombings of 2002. He is also suspected of plotting attacks on the Australian Embassy and J.W. Marriott hotel. Court declared Jemaah Islamiyah a terrorist organization Monday.

Anthropologist reconstructs Neanderthal vocal tracts to simulate their voice. Result is a single syllable that sounds like a frog croaking or a human burping. Neanderthals lacked "quantal vowels" modern humans use, anthropologist says. He plans to simulate an entire Neanderthal sentence.

"Flash-bang" grenades were relabeled and sold to police after Navy deemed them faulty. Indictment alleges company officials bribed a federal official and paid for a strip club. Company, known as PSI, did not immediately respond to calls for comment.

Pentagon had contracts with three companies with ties to Warren Jeffs' sect. Some of the deals were made after Jeffs was named to the FBI's "Most-Wanted List" Jeffs is serving time in Utah after his 2007 conviction for being an accomplice to rape. Private investigator says dozens of companies tied to Jeffs are working on contracts.

U.S. military in Japan has charged a Marine with rape and other violations. Staff Sgt. Tyrone Luther Hadnott, 38, is accused of raping a 14-year-old girl. The rape accusation stirred memories of a brutal rape more than a decade ago. Prime Minister Yasuo Fukuda deplored as "unforgivable"

NEW: Sen. Barack Obama says Sen. Hillary Clinton is "toughening" him up. NEW: Obama mocks Clinton for throwing back a shot of whiskey in front of TV crews. Clinton has been hitting Obama hard after he referred to some small-town Pennsylvanians as "bitter"

Germany striker Kevin Kuranyi scores the only goal as Schalke beat Hamburg 1-0. Werder Bremen share a thrilling 3-3 draw with Karlsruhe. Bayern Munich can go 12 points clear with a win over Stuttgart on Sunday. Nuremberg and Arminia Bielefeld draw 1-1 to stay bottom of the table.

Mohtarma Benazir Bhutto died after being attacked during a political rally in Rawalpindi. Only apparent injury was a major trauma to the right side of the head. UK experts exclude this injury being an entry or exit wound as a result of gunshot.

Storms that killed two people in northern Georgia spread Saturday night into South Carolina. Possible tornadoes downed trees, blew roofs off homes and broke power lines. Woman severely injured when a tree fell on her trailer, trapping her inside. About 56,000 customers remained without power Sunday morning.

Iraqi report on Blackwater shootings calls incident "pre-meditated murder" Report calls for $8 million in compensation for each of the 17 Iraqis who died. Report will be presented to Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki's government for review. Blackwater security contractors were guarding a State Department convoy.

NEW: Bill Clinton denies saying Obama campaign played the race card on him. NEW: Clinton: "You really got to go some to try to portray me as a racist" Clinton compared Obama's showing in South Carolina to that of Jesse Jackson. Obama says he has no idea what Clinton meant.

Fight breaks out at opening of massive Gadhafi National Mosque in Kampala. Ugandan and Libyan presidential guards fight during ceremony attended by heads of state. No leaders were hurt in the melee, though several were knocked over. Libyan and Ugandan protocol officials trade bitter accusations of disrespect.

Female suicide bomber apparently targeting Shiite worshippers kills at least 40. Karbala is a Shiite holy city, and the Imam Hussein shrine is one of Shiite Islam's holiest locations. U.S. Vice President Dick Cheney arrives in the Iraqi capital on an unannounced visit.

Nadia Comaneci was the first gymnast in history to score a perfect 10. The 14-year-old Romanian won three gold medals at the 1976 Montreal Games. She was honored as a Hero of Socialist Labor on her return home. In 2000 she was named one of the athletes of the century by Laureus World Sports Academy.

Michigan is a swing state, producing narrow margins of victory for presidential candidates. Top-tier Democratic candidates have taken their names off the ballot. The state's economy is powered by the automotive industry. Michigan's unemployment rate, 7.4 percent, is higher than the national average of 5%.

NEW: Four U.S. soldiers killed when vehicle hit by IED in Baghdad. NEW: A fifth soldier wounded in the attack, which took place about 10 p.m. (3 p.M. ET) NEW: News of the 4,000 mark came on the same day that Iraq's national security adviser urged Americans to be patient with the progress of the war. Nearly 160,000 American troops remain in Iraq, and the war has cost about $

Adam Gilchrist will retire from cricket at the end of the Australian summer. The 36-year-old chose Australia Day to make his decision public. Gilchrist broke the world record for the most wicketkeeping dismissals in Tests. Australia reached 322-3 at stumps on the third day of the fourth Test in Adelaide.

Javier Zanetti scores a late volley to earn Inter Milan a 1-1 draw against Roma. Francesco Totti had given the visitors a deserved first-half lead. The draw maintains Inter's nine-point lead at the top of Serie A. AC Milan slipped to fifth place as they were held to a 1 -1 draw at Catania.

Jean-Claude Darcheville and Nacho Novo both score twice as Rangers beat Hearts. Rangers win 4-0 to maintain four-point lead at top of Scottish Premier League. Scott McDonald and Georgios Samaras score as Celtic beat Inverness 2-1.

Rozita Swinton, 33, has been arrested in a case that is not directly related to the Texas raid. Texas Rangers have said she is a person of interest in connection with the ranch calls. Calls in late March prompted authorities to raid the Yearning For Zion (YFZ) Ranch.

Victor Manuel Mejia Munera was one of Colombia's most sought-after criminals. He was wearing an American-style, desert-camouflage uniform when he was killed. He and his brother have been accused of running major drug rings in Colombia. The brothers also have faced narcotics-trafficking charges in the United States.

Some Democrats fear their party's method of picking a nominee might turn undemocratic. Party rules call for the votes of superdelegates to tip the balance. The party instituted the system to avoid the turmoil that a deadlocked race would create. Superdelegates are free to vote however they want.

Most children show signs they're ready to potty train between 18 and 24 months. For some kids, the toilet training process can take more than a year, or longer. A six-week program at Children's Hospital Boston is one of a handful around the country. A majority of the children who attend the class are dealing with constipation.

"Grand Theft Auto IV" expected to set sales records in gaming world this week. Some speculate that game will put a dent in opening weekend box office for "Iron Man" "GTA IV" is the ninth incarnation of a video game in which the user acts as a criminal.

NEW: Bobby Cutts Jr. apologizes, asks jury to spare his life. NEW: "I pray that you find peace and you someday find room for forgiveness," he says. Cutts was convicted on February 15 of the murder of girlfriend Jessie Marie Davis. He was also convicted of the aggravated murder of Davis' unborn daughter.

NEW: "The impact was direct. The aircraft is practically pulverized," firefighter says. Plane went missing while flying from Merida to the international airport near Caracas. The pilot did not check in with controllers 20 minutes into the flight, as scheduled. Witnesses saw the Santa Barbara Airlines plane go down, an official says.

Man dressed as a priest caught at Amsterdam's airport with three kilos of cocaine. Police stopped the man as he was transiting on a flight from South America. He refused to be searched saying that he was a religious person. Dutch police trying to establish if the man is a real priest after he claimed to be senior member of clergy.

A Los Angeles, California, lawyer has come up with a series of cards geared toward prison inmates. Some express simple good wishes: "We are all praying for you while you do your time" Others dole out tough love: "When you called last time, I was not very sympathetic" More than 2.3 million people were in jails or prisons in the United States in 2008.

Final chapter in Microsoft's acclaimed video game series hit shelves at midnight. Xbox 360 game expected to shatter entertainment sales records within first 24 hours. CNN.com readers offer comparisons to "Star Wars" and "Harry Potter" "Halo" is not just a game, it's a lifestyle, a booming culture, fans say.

Courtney Larrell Lockhart, 23, of Smiths, Alabama, charged with capital murder. Burk, 18, from Marietta, Georgia, was found shot on Tuesday night. Police found a car -- which turned out to be Burk's -- on fire in a lot.

"Desperate Housewife" star Tony Parker shares what's in her closet. Her favorite dress is a "gorgeous 1950s-style cocktail dress by Gustavo Cadile" Most expensive item is a hot-pink crocodile HermÃ¨s Birkin bag.

NEW: Kenyan environmental activist Wangari Maathai places first seeds inside vault. Svalbard Global Seed Vault is located 130 meters (427 feet) inside a frozen mountain. The vault sits at the end of a 120-meter (131-yard) tunnel blasted inside the mountain. Eventually the vault will hold 4.5 million distinct samples of seeds.

White students at South Africa's Free State University make racist video. Video shows black housekeepers eating stew containing urine. Protesters march to residence where video was made, demand it be shut down. University officials and human rights groups in South Africa denounce the video, which surfaced Tuesday.

Tornado damages trees, power lines, overturns 18-wheel truck in Tupelo, Mississippi. Mall at Barnes Crossing sustained "minor property damage," general manager says. Airport closed for about 10 minutes while taxiway and runway were cleared. No reports of injuries; authorities assessing damages.

Saudi Arabia is awash in cash which keeps pouring into the world's largest oil producer. Last year alone, Saudi is estimated to have raked in about $200 billion from oil. Inflation is currently running at 9.6 percent -- a 30-year high. The kingdom's business community is concerned about the adverse effects of inflation.

Sen. Barack Obama: Most important thing would be to deal with Iraq, al Qaeda in Afghanistan. Obama says U.S. influence around the world has been diminishing. Sen. Hillary Clinton would win West Virginia primary by "big margin," Obama says. Obama deflected question about a potential joint ticket with Clinton.

Lufthansa flight scrapes wing during landing attempt in Hamburg, Germany. Dramatic amateur video of the incident appeared on the Internet. Plane recovered and landed safely the second time around, airline says. Damage to plane was minimal and not structural, airline spokesman says.

Richard Leith, 64, was babysitting his grandchild in the home. Both were transported to local hospitals, though Leith died later in the afternoon. The condition of the child, who was treated at Children's Hospital, is unknown. Several neighboring homes were damaged.

Dutch tourist says she recently spotted missing 4-year-old Madeleine McCann. Spokesman: She and a friend saw a child that they immediately took to be madeleine. A man who was with the child scooped the child up and took her out of the cafe. Police watched the closed-circuit video footage, an official says.

Ortega: "We are breaking with the terrorist policies that the government of [Colombian President] Alvaro Uribe is practicing" Ecuador has broken off relations with Colombia, and Venezuela says it has moved troops to its border with Colombia. Organization of American States passed a resolution Wednesday in hopes of easing tensions.

Five young men killed when car drove off end of private airstrip near Ocala, Florida. Car became airborne for 200 feet and slammed into an oak tree. All of the victims were declared dead at the scene. "This had to be the worst vehicle crash that I have ever seen"

Police dogs in Duesseldorf, Germany are now patrolling the pavement in protective shoes. The reason? Too many glass shards left by beer drinkers in the city center. Glass poses a problem for the police force's 20 German Shepherds and Belgian ShepherDS. Dogs need a month of training to get used to wearing the shoes.

U.N. anti-drugs chief denounces celebrities such as Amy Winehouse and Kate Moss. Antonio Maria Costa says alleged drug use is helping devastate West Africa. Comments published in opinion piece in British newspaper The Observer. Winehouse's spokesman calls Costa a "ludicrous man"

Fight breaks out at opening of massive Gadhafi National Mosque in Kampala. Ugandan and Libyan presidential guards fight during ceremony attended by heads of state. No leaders were hurt in the melee, though several were knocked over. Libyan and Ugandan protocol officials traded bitter accusations of disrespect and racism.

Lionel Messi will be out of action for six weeks after tearing a muscle in his left leg. Messi picked up the injury after 34 minutes during Barcelona's 1-0 victory over Celtic. It is third time in the last three years that Messi has had the same injury.

Remains of adult and fetus found in shallow grave in backyard of suspect. Cpl. Cesar Armando Laurean charged with first-degree murder in Marine's death. Laurean, 21, of Nevada, is believed to be driving a black Dodge pickup. Marine disappeared when she was eight months pregnant.

NEW: U.S. Embassy in Belgrade evacuating nonessential personnel. NEW: Spokesman says embassy will remain closed until Monday or Tuesday. U.s. ambassador, Cameron Munter, is staying, officials say. Violence erupted after demonstrations by thousands of Serbs against independence.

Authorities confirmed Tuesday that captive animals in two of China's major panda reserves were alive. Concern arose in the international wildlife community over damage to the animals' habitat. The mountainous, densely wooded region is the natural habitat for most of the 1,200 giant pandas.

NEW: With 99 percent of precincts in, Clinton has 54 percent of the vote in Ohio. NEW: Obama leads Clinton 56 percent to 44 percent in Texas caucuses. Clinton wins Ohio, Rhode Island, Vermont primaries. Clinton had been expected to do well in Ohio, where blue-collar workers support her.

wire was about 4 feet high when pulled tight, or about neck level for an ATV. "It was configured in a way so that, if it was pulled, it would take off the head of a Border Patrol agent," official says. Officials suspected that drug or illegal immigrant smugglers were involved.

NEW: Sen. Hillary Clinton congratulates Sen. Barack Obama. NEW: Former Sen. John Edwards says he's "in this for the long haul" With 99 percent of precincts reporting, Obama had 55 percent of the vote. Clinton was second with 27 percent, followed by Edwards with 18 percent.

Jamiel Shaw, 17, was shot to death in Los Angeles on March 2. Gang members asked him if he was in a gang, police say; he didn't have time to say "no" Pedro Espinoza, a 19-year-old member of the Hispanic 18th Street Gang, charged. Police chief calls on community to help police locate a second suspect.

Lewis Hamilton is set to become one of the most marketable sport stars in the world. The 23-year-old signed a five-year contract with McLaren worth an estimated $140m. If he can maintain the buzz created by his first season in Formula One he will earn more than Michael Schumacher.

Red Cross President and CEO Mark W. Everson steps down after revelations. He was "engaged in a personal relationship with a subordinate employee" Everson, 53, said he was leaving the $500,000-per-year job "for personal and family reasons" Board of governors appointed Mary S. Elcano, general counsel, as interim president.

Most of Canada's 2,500 troops in Afghanistan are in Kandahar province. The Canadian mission in Afghanistan was to end next February. Supporters of the mission argue that Canadians have made progress. The cost of maintaining a troop presence in Afghanistan has not been disclosed to the public.

Police dogs in Duesseldorf, Germany are now patrolling the pavement in protective shoes. The reason? Too many glass shards left by beer drinkers in the city center. Glass poses a problem for the police force's 20 German Shepherds and Belgian ShepherDS. Dogs need a month of training to get used to wearing the shoes.

Barcelona are ready for twice world player of the year Ronaldinho to move on. Brazilian midfielder struggled with injuries and poor form last season. AC Milan showed an interest in signing him and his brother Robert De Assis said personal terms had been agreed but the clubs failed to reach agreement.

Immigration and Customs Enforcement releases more than 100 photos of Halloween party. One photo shows an employee in prison stripes, dreadlocks and face-darkening makeup. ICE chief Julie Myers ordered the photos deleted because they were inappropriate. Sen. Claire McCaskill put a "hold" on Myers' confirmation because of the hubbub.

NEW: Hazardous materials teams are still cleaning up a toxic chemical spill. NEW: "Hazmat says that clean up is moving quickly and on track," Lafayette police say. Two train cars leaked highly corrosive hydrochloric acid after a derailment. The spill caused a toxic cloud to form above the site.
